text.0: Mortal Reins What is Mortal Reins? Mortal Reins is a roleplaying game - somewhere between a wargame, simulation and improv theater. Between two and as many as you can logistically cram (We recommend four or five)  players go on to create a dramatic story together, with one player taking the role of the Game Master, who will act out the world with all its dangers and people, while the others will take the role of Characters - adventurers looking to leave their mark on the world, free agents whose struggles will become reality for the players. Mortal Reins is a dark fantasy - one where morality is gray, fights are quick and brutal and monsters are to be feared and avoided. The world at large is crumbling, and the players aren’t even trying to put back the pieces, just scrambling to not get crushed on the way down. What do you need? Y ou need: · An active imagination, · Some paper and pencils (at least 1 per player, and a few spare pages for the GM) · At least 2 Ten sided dice, later referred to in the rules as just dice, or d10’s. These are used whenever a player or GM faces an outcome with multiple potential dramatic outcomes. · Tokens to represent players, who goes first and tracking ‘ Advantage’ - points given to the players to affect their rolls to represent preparation and having the upper hand. How do you play? After creating the players create their characters and setting, the GM player will set a scene and allow each of the other characters in order to describe their actions. If it is necessary, the GM will call for a skill check roll from the character players. Based on the results of the skill check, the GM will tell them how their action succeeded or failed and how this changes the scene. The next player then describes their action, and so on until the characters retire, or die. How is it different? Mortal Reins is a darker and more grounded roleplaying game than many of its ilk. It is as often a depowering or horrifying experience as it is a power fantasy. The choices the character players make are real and meaningful, but the game is stacked against them and they know it.
text.4: Basic Rules Making a Game Each game of Mortal Reins is unique to the players in it. It can be a party of roguish charming monster hunt- ers running through the dark woods in search of the dragon’s daughter or a group of thieves planning heists in a capital city, or a band of merry men who have found the aforementioned dragon’s daughter, and now want to set her up as empress in a series of political schemes. The following section will take you through the steps of making a setting and characters to play with in Mortal Reins. Making a Setting While Mortal Reins can support any sort of fantasy world, it works best at a place that is a flashpoint of conflict in a world already teetering on the brink. One such world is detailed in the lore section, and the rest of the rules assume your adventures take place in that world. It’s nothing but a backdrop for the adventure you think of however. The actual setting is a much more specific area of the world, fleshed out by the players with details that they have thought of. Keep in mind that you can alter as much or as little of that world as you want, or even start from scratch, it’ll just take extra work creating everything and getting everyone on the same page. On the other hand, for some people that’s half the fun. What to keep Strife Mortal Reins shines when the world is in a state of flux. Chaos is the name of the game, and the world should be recoiling from civil wars, ravaged by monsters and ripped apart by forces within and without - Civilization is being put to the test, and it is being found wanting. Wealth inequality The system represents a world in which money is king - sometimes literally. A person who has the money to dish out is respected, while even a powerful warrior or expert leader is laughed at if they don’t have the social class to back up their skills. The people are depraved and their leaders corrupt. Late antiquity technology The age of sword and spear is here, and while armor exists it’s also heavy and clunky. The crossbow has just been invented, but has not reached mass production; the gun has not even been thought of as an idea.
text.9: Basic Rules Making a Company Take a second to discuss why your characters work together rather than alone. This can be as simple as being allies of convenience, or as complex as a shadow cult, family ties, or a formal business contract. Characters can be extremely different in Mortal Reins so some guidance can be useful when making them so they don’t drift apart. This is also a good place to have a conversation about how unified you want your characters to act, and whether you want inter party conflict or not. The tighter the company is, the less opportunities there are for such conflict, but the less creative freedom each player has over their personal character. Goals Given the shared themes and issues of the setting, what are some of the goals of your company, and what type of character would think it a good idea to join such a company. Modus Operandi What does the group do when faced with an issue on obstacle, as a general rule. Keep this section broad and brief, but give some general guidance to what type of characters would be useful to the company. Assets / Affiliation / Antagonists Any power groups that your company has tangled with in the past or any assets that your company has obtained. When first starting out, this section can be skipped, and later built up from the character conflicts, or it can be built up first, with the character conflicts then building off of the company to be more specific. First Meeting The characters first meeting can be roleplayed out but often its easier to have it described in the background so the game can focus on the plot; Either way it’s important for the players to know how long they’re known the other characters to decide their relationships with them and how much they know about each other in character. Setting a Playstyle The most important part of the company is deciding on a playstyle for the group. Each character will take a different spin on this, but a Math Teacher Courtesier will feel overwhelmed in fighting a Troll after hiking through the wildreness for weeks in the same way as a Brawly Tribal Barbarian will be out of place at a ball representing a political party. Some variety will always naturally occur, but all the players including the Game Master should set their expectations here.
text.10: Making a Character Now knowing the issues of the settings and the methods of your company, you can make your own personal character.  This is covered in more detail in the Creating Characters Section. Mortal Reins is a character driven game, and it’s important for the characters to be Relevant to the setting and Proactive in their goals. Relevant Characters Characters should tie in some way to the setting. While it’s possible to have a generic character that can apply to any world, it’s much more satisfying when the character is connected to the world the Game Master is manipulating, and allows for more strings to be pulled and plot threads unraveled. Proactive Characters Characters should always have a goal in mind; which is relatively specific and not all encompassing. Characters without a goal can turn out to be aimless and not progress the story without the Game Master’s prompting, while Characters with too broad a goal can face a similar issue, paralyzed by the choices available to them or fleeting back and forth between different objectives without accomplishing a single one. Realistic Characters It can be tempting when creating a character to give them an epic backstory that ties into all the powers in the world and establishes a lore and history for the character. Unless otherwise specified in the Making a company and playstyle step, this is a mistake: the default starting power level of characters in MR is quite modest, and the dichotomy between the feats described in the backstory and what is actually possible for the character can make for some cognitive dissonance. In any case creating characters is also part of the game and a cooperative endeavor, so the best approach is to discuss your backstory with the other players. Content warning: Making Respect Mortal Reins is by its nature a freeform storytelling game that handles mature themes, including violence of different kinds, oppression, death. These themes are powerful, and can create strong stories, but they can also make players deeply uncomfortable. It’s important to understand that everyone at the table might have completely different tolerances for such content: One might be willing to genocide whole tribes of people but get triggered when psychological manipulation reminds them of something in real life. Someone can enjoy meting out violence and their own brand of justice, but totally fold psychologically when the other shoe drops and it’s them lying in a pool of guts and blood on the floor. A group might exclude all sexual undertones from their story, or they might do a fade to black when the situation gets to the appropriate moment, or roleplay out sexual encounters and orgies with skill checks and narration. At the end of the day, this is just a book - it’s not going to judge what stories you and your friends tell around the table. As long as everyone remains civil to each other it should be an enjoyable experience. That said if you haven’t discussed these topics with the other players before and don’t know their tolerance for such things, it might be worthwhile to have a conversation before introducing such elements to the table - it’s better to talk it out in a civil manner than have an argument with emotions running hot.
text.11: Basic Rules Playing the Game: Basic Rules The game is played conversationally, with the Game Master setting a scene - describing a location, the characters therein and any sights, smells and sounds the player characters encounter. The players in turn narrate what they do  in the scene; The Game Master tells them the result of their actions, and this repeats ad infinitum. The players may want to narrate their actions in first or third person, and they may want to create a voice for their character complete with quirks and accents; or they may not. As long as everyone at the table understands the context of what’s happening in the story anything is fine. Some groups might prefer to have a diagram and maps on hand to show the relative positions of everyone in the company, while others keep everything in their mind, or do something in between. If figurines and maps are used, we recommend 1cm of real world space to be 1 meter in game, or 1 inch of real space to be 2 meters. Each character in the game is represented by a collection of skills and statistics that represent what they are good at and capable of, and the players use the dice in combination with their character sheets to play out scenarios with some degree of uncertainty. Staying in Character The degree to which players will stay in character ultimately depends on the individual group, and as long as everyone at the table is happy it’s okay. It’s often more fun and exciting to get into the role of the character. For example when speaking the player should say the words the character says instead of describing an action like “Sset tells the rest of the characters about the thing I found out. ” Firstly, it helps keep the players engaged, but also specifics are important - the other characters might respond to information in different ways depending on how it is presented. Likewise, when describing actions it’s worthwhile to go into a little detail behind the intent and execution of an action, as this helps the other players and Game Master react appropriately to what is being described.
text.18: Skill Check Most of the game can be done conversationally, in a back and forth manner as the characters describe what they are doing and the Game master describes the world’s reaction, sometimes in a scene multiple avenues are dramatically interesting. When such an opportunity occurs, the character player makes a skill check. Whenever you need to make a roll or skill check, you choose a specialty that is applicable to the situation. Combine the bonus from the specialty (+3 for every point spent), the skill (+2 for every point spent) and the stat bonus (relevant statistic bonus modifier) Roll 2 dice. Y ou will always add the lowest of the two dice (Average roll of 4) to the relevant bonus. However, you may modify the dice using Advantage points, re rolling dice, changing the values and adding to the total as described in the Fate and Advantage section on the next page. There are some concepts to keep in mind with skill checks: A skill check can only be made once until circumstances change. A lock that isn’t picked can’t be picked again, a jump that isn’t made can’t be tried again, and forbidden lore that is too complicated to read can’t be understood. On the other hand, players should fail forward. The story shouldn’t come to a standstill based on the results of dice. When a player fails they should suffer a consequence, but the game should continue. In the examples above, The lock can be opened given enough time, the jump can have an adventurer fall down a few stories before they catch themselves on the far side, and the forbidden texts can be read in a sufficiently advanced library. Don’t roll unless an action is opposed or difficult to do. If the GM’s first instinct for difficulty is lower than the character’s skill then the character automatically passes - if it is higher than they can possibly roll, then the character recognizes the folly and doesn’t try the action, unless the player indicates they want to try anyway and have enough advantage. Roll difficulty - 5 easy 7 moderate 10 challenging 12 difficult 15 very hard 20 mythical 25 legendaryCritical Success or Failure
text.26: Basic Rules Fate Fate represents your character’s ability to impact the world in excess of the limitations of their mortal body, pulled along by the whims of destiny to do great things. Each character starts with 2 Fate points, unless modified by their race or game master. Fate can be used for one of four things: · Automatically replace the value rolled on a die or skill check roll at any one time to a 15. Ignore the fact that rolling a 15 on a ten sided die is impossible. Appreciate the possibilities. · Automatically fail a roll you choose, even if it were trivial for you to succeed. This is primarily useful if you want to kill a character who means no immediate harm to yours, but can be used in any situation where you want your character not to succeed a roll. · Escape death when your character has reached negative body points and the story permits their survival and being left for dead. This might be impossible if the character’s body isn’t intact at the end of the death, such as a beheading or digestion. Fate is never restored; once a point is used, it is used forever. Characters can achieve new Fate points when they achieve their dream or such a significant milestone towards it that the Game Master is impressed, usually at the end of a campaign. Advantage Points Unlike Fate, Advantage is fleeting, coming and going back and forth multiple times in a scene. It represents your character’s ability to manipulate events to their advantage by being more aware, acute or in a better position than their opponents. Advantage is gained when you use the “Improve situation” action or when the Game Master determines you are in a position that automatically offers advantage, such as: · Having the high ground · Outflanking an opponent · Attacking a restrained or prone target · Speaking to someone in their own language, that is not the common tongue of the land. · Making a good point through impassioned speech · Anything else the GM approves. Advantage can also be removed. Y ou lose all your advantage points when you
text.42: Ex. Carmen attempts to strike at Marco. She rolls a 2 on one die and 5 on the other, with her skill bonus of +5, that would mean a 7. Since Marco has a dodge of 7, she misses. However, Carmen has several advantage points. She could spend a point to make her 7 into a 9, beating Marco, but she knows he also has advantage and could dodge that attack, so instead she re-rolls the 2 and gets a 6! Now the 5 is her lowest die, so she would hit with a score of 10, but she’s not satisfied. Using another point of advantage she lowers the 6 into a second 5. Now her dice have the same result, meaning a critical hit and a wound on Marco, unless he parries… Disadvantage If you are disadvantaged - narratively or from taking damage to a limb for example - Y ou cannot use advantage on the roll, and must subtract 2 from the result. A disadvantage can occur from: · Doing two things at once, such as treading water and fighting someone · Doing things without your senses, in the dark or bound · Not knowing the same language while interacting Soft scene reset At the GM’s discretion, when a scene calls for a change but they want to keep the player’s momentum going (such as when an investigation turns into a chase or a social interaction turns into a combat) the characters can keep 1 or 2 advantage points. Strings Strings represent the sum of a character’s interaction with another character which improves their ability to manipulate them. They can mean anything from blackmail to memories of good times together. For every String a character has on another, they get a free advantage on that interaction. Strings can be gained when: · The GM awards one for a piece of manipulatory information or good interaction · The player takes a String on another character through social interaction Strings can be lost when: · The player uses the String outside of social interaction to get an advantage on a combat check on the character · They are given up as part of a deal with the character to make them act as you want them to

text.44: Unless there is an opposition to the players, it’s not necessary to create a formal scene - it is assumed the characters will succeed given enough time or a task will be impossible for them. Only when they run into a situation where time is critical or someone means them harm is it important to establish a turn order and set the stakes of the scene: usually these are implicit, like a giant spider coming for your life, but sometimes it’s better to hash these things out like “This merchant wants a better price, but he’s not willing to risk his life for it” Scenes flow from one to another smoothly as soon as one side achieves its objectives or the conflict stops making sense. When a scene ends, all the accumulated advantage is lost. Make sure to talk about the timescale of a conflict. For physical combat this is generally 12 seconds per turn, while a chase through the streets can have up to 5 minutes per turn and a legal battle can go on for many hours or even days!. Roaming This is the most common mode of play, one where the player characters are not in conflict with anyone. It is not a scene by itself, more the absence of a scene. The GM can still choose to make the players roll for certain actions, but they don’t have to give out advantage points if they don’t think the action will result in a meaningful advantage to the character; For example if the character wants to know some background Lore information that wouldn’t be directly relevant or they want to scavenge for supplies without time pressure - in that case only the result of the roll matters, without passing advantage around. There are no defined turns in Roaming play, with the narrative passing to whoever feels the most relevant at the time. This can be a complicated job for the Game Master, especially if the players are separated by space or time, so some amount of faith in each other as players is required for everyone to get equal screen time. Any character can perform any amount of actions as long as the GM has focus on them.
text.53: Basic Rules Pursuit In a pursuit scene, One side is attempting to disengage while another is trying to get to them, which can rep- resent a dash through the streets to catch a thief or a quest for unrequited love.First, determine how long the scene will be - a good number is 3 successes for a short chase and 5 for an involved one. In a physical chase, the character with the faster speed gets a point of advantage every turn, and if they dou- ble the speed of the other party they get 2 advantage points every turn.  Starting with the creature attempting to escape, the players decide on a course of action they take to escape or change the environment, which can cause an issue for the pursuers the following. The other party determines what they do to respond to the challenge and roll a relevant skill test. When a group is running away or chasing, they have the speed of their weakest member unless they want to split up. The other members of the group can offer advantage by helping their slowest.All members contribute to a group pool of advantage points when they roll, but only the lowest roll matters when compared to the other group to see who gets ahead in the chase. Any member of the group can attack or cast a spell at the other group if they are in range. If it is a ranged attack, the other group gets two advantages and an automatic success like if they rolled unopposed and suc-ceeded; if it is a melee attack the attacker also needs to expend an advantage from their group pool to attempt to hitThe first group to get an amount of successes equal to the scene length wins the chase, either getting away or catching up to their target. Challenge A challenge scene is a Communal effort to do something with a passive opposition - Time or Environment or Knowledge. The Game Master must establish a limited number of attempts or an opposing side to a challenge - otherwise assume it is either impossible or can be done by the characters. Alternatively the Game Master can set the stakes of the rolls such as taking damage if failing a roll while climbing.
text.58: Basic Rules They represent the general physical, emotional and intellectual fitness of a character. For most characters these will be in the range 1 to 10, though some exceptions might occur. They offer a bonus to the roll equal to the Statistic - 5 (With an average 5/10 giving the character a +0 bonus) Strength (Abbreviated to STR) - Strength is a measure of how tough, strong and scary you are. Characters with a high strength are physically large, imposing and able to smash and throw things both unarmed and with weapons, use weapons like the greatsword or longbow that require physical strength, absorb punishment, lift and carry heavy loads, survive deadly perils. Characters with a low strength are comparatively sickly, weak, physically unintimidating. Dexterity (Abbreviated to DEX) - Dexterity is a measure of how quick and adept you are, and how in control of your own body you can be. Characters with a high dexterity are able to nimbly navigate difficult environments, swim, climb, accurately hit targets with both melee and ranged weapons, notice things and react to them faster, hide themselves from sight and perform complicated sleight of hand like opening locks. Characters with a low dexterity are clumsy, oaf-like, inattentive. Intelligence (Abbreviated to INT) - Intelligence is a measure of how smart and wise you are. Characters with a high Intelligence know more history and can deduce more from the clues around them, as well as articulate their point more effectively. They are less likely to get lost and are more likely to have the right tool for the job at any particular time and to be able to craft something if they do not. Characters with a low Intelligence are simple, less knowledgeable and worldly. Empathy (Abbreviated to EMP) - Empathy is a measure of how you can both understand and manipulate people. Characters with a high Empathy are better at reading the room, saying the right thing and being friends with people, as well as making up stories and convincing lies when necessary. They also are more in tune with the world, magical energies and handling animals. Characters with a low empathy are more likely to make social faux pas, be crude and oafish.
text.62: Skills get increased by +2 per 1 point spent. The first point costs 1 XP for +2, then 2XP for +4 and finally 3XP for a +6 in the skill. They are added to the Statistic Bonus when rolling a skill check, so a Character with a +1 bonus in Strength and 1 point in Smash  and 2 points in Physique would roll a +3 to Smash and +5 to Physique. Smash (str) Break stuff, and people. Use your strength coupled with weapons or other tools to attack some target. Some weapons, like heavy axes and hammers are only used using the smash skill. Accuracy (dex) Use your superior reflexes and training to use weapons and other items to punch, slash or shoot or throw something at another character. Some weapons, like a spear or rapier, light draw small bow, a crossbow or blowgun can be used using the accuracy skill. Aim at targets using your manual dexterity. Also used for throwing light objects, like small knives or bottles. Mobility(dex) Use your mastery of your body to move, climb, swim or free run through difficult terrain. This skill can be used anywhere your flexibility, nimbleness and strength to weight ratio matter more than your absolute strength. Can also represent fancy footwork during a fight like rolling or a riposte. Launch(str) Launch a projectile using your strength. Used for drawing heavy bowstrings and throwing heavy objects, things like larger weapons, axes and boulders. Athletics (str) Y our ability to navigate and affect the environment using your strength; jumping, running, lifting things up. This is also the skill to increase to move faster when running and sprinting. This skill also increases the amount of items you can carry on your person before you are encumbered. Thievery (dex) Y our ability to enter places that would prefer to keep you out - lockpicking, casing a place or person for weaknesses. This skill also covers any sleight of hand you may attempt, pickpocketing or playing subtle tricks using your fingers, dexterity and subterfuge. Animal handling(emp) Y our ability to care for animals, charm and train them. Also used to ride animals or drive wagons.
text.71: Basic Rules Notice (dex) Y our ability to perceive things and initiative to act on them. At the beginning of a scene, the character with the highest notice roll goes first. Physique (str) Y our physical toughness. Used to weather extreme conditions, pick up heavy objects, and your body points, which determine how much abuse you can weather before you fall unconscious. Provoke (str) Y our ability to intimidate and unnerve someone or provoke them to action, whether through your appearance, shouting or banging on your shield. Can be used to motivate friends or harm enemies. Rapport (emp) Y our ability to make friends and acquaintances, as well as your fame and presence. Y ou can also use it to inspire your friends or sway your opponents. This is your default Empathy skill. Much like Resourcefulness can be used retroactively “Do I know anyone in this town/organization” or used to pull strings for you. It can be used to communicate with someone you know Resourcefulness (int) Y our ability to bargain, barter and scrounge up something that you packed away for just this moment. Can be used in a flashback manner like “Of course my character probably thought to bring torches, he’s resourceful!” in which case the item must be commonplace and you must pay the price immediately. Stealth (dex) Y our ability to hide yourself and dodge out of trouble. Can be used to cover up tracks and hide in cover. This isn’t invisibility, but if you find a place to hide it allows you to cover yourself and move silently. This is also the skill which affects your Dodge rating, which is your defense when you are getting physically attacked. Willpower (emp) Y our ability to maintain cool despite crazy and stressful things happening to you. Also used for your mind points, which determine how much stress you can take before you give up, whether that’s from social interactions, dodging physical attacks or casting magics. Mysticism (emp) Y our ability to commune with natural magic currents, spirits and gods. Can be used to communicate with powers beyond the mortal plane, find lost souls, touch on the magical lines that cover the world, understand the arcane and holy.
text.76: Basic Rules Special skills Fate - Represents your ability to get out of problems that would kill a normal person. Can be permanently burned to take a 15 on a roll or ignore a wound or anxiety. Advantage - Fleeting number gained through combat. Can be used to reroll a die, subtract 1 from it or add 2 to the resulting number. Lost at the end of a scene. Gained by improving the situation or situational effects (outnumbering) Defensive Ratings - These are the numbers opponents need to beat with their skill check to affect you Dodge [Stealth-Dodge / 2 + 7] What people need to beat to physically hit you Perception [Notice-Perception / 2 + 7] What people need to beat to sneak past youConsider [Reasoning-Consider / 2 + 7] What people need to beat to mentally affect you Resource Pools - These are used up as your character becomes more and more tired Body [10 + Physique: Body Points] How much abuse your body can takeMind [10 + Willpower: Mind Points] How much abuse your mind can takeArcana [Lore: Arcane Points] Extra mind points to affect the immaterial plane Y our Consider, Body and Mind ratings are improved by an increased Social Strata, discussed in the Advanced Rules section In physical combat you can use Mind or Body to avoid damage. Mind represents your ability to narrowly miss a strike on your vitals while being stressed out while Body represents scrapes, bruises and other small injuries that heal in a short time. Y ou can use either point to take damage. Running out of body points leads to a knockout of the character, potentially leading to death. In social combat only Mind points are used. Running out of Mind points your character is exhausted and unwilling to participate in any form of discussion, debate or plan making. They’re not necessarily convinced but they can’t oppose the other entity anymore. When casting spells , a caster can use points from either their Arcana or Mind pools Comfortable Carry - how much stuff can your character carry on their person without breaking a sweat, in
text.89: Quadrupeds Creatures that make use of  all four limbs to move around double their move speed, but cannot make use of any tools, and are unable to run or sprint over terrain that would require a biped character to make a mobility roll to get over. In addition, Quadruped creatures can be ridden by those of a size smaller than them with no penalties. Winged Creatures Character have a size rating. The size for a normal human sized creature is size 1 for 70-150kg Things that are larger are have a size Number 2 to 5, here listed as N · Size 3 is a troll or bear, 200 - 500 kg · Size 5 is a small dragon or giant - 2-3 tons · Creatures above size 2 Can attack N-1 targets if they’re next to each other with one attack action. · Body points multiply by N (Round Up) · Carry amount and encumbrance multiplies by N (Round Up) · +(N-1) to Attack damage (+1 for Size 2, +2 for Size 3, etc) · - (N-1) to dodge (-1 for Size 2, -2 for Size 3, etc) · The cost of living increases by N times (2x for Size 2, 3x for Size 2, etc) · Price of Gear increases by N * 2 times (4x for Size 2, 6x for Size 3, etc) The largest thing covered by this is a Size 5 creature. Creatures and Things beyond this are not covered by creature rules. Smaller things have a fractional size 1/5 to ½ where the denominator is N · Size ½ is a large dog or goblin, 30-60 kg · Size ¼ is a fairy or bird, 5-10 kg · Body points divided by N (Round Up) · Carry amount and encumbrance divided by N (Round Up) · +(N-1) to Dodge (+1 for Size 2, +2 for Size 3, etc) · - (N-1) to Attack Damage (-1 for Size 2, -2 for Size 3, etc) · The cost of living decreases by N times (1/2x for Size 1/2, 1/3x for Size 1/3, etc) · Price of Gear decreases by N times (1/2x for Size 2, 1/3x for Size 3, etc) The smallest fraction of size is 1/5, which is a squirrel or an average item 1-2 kg . text.91: Basic Rules Turn Order Most of the time a free form order works out best, but when the order of actions is important, establish in what turn each player goes. Each player rolls Notice- initiative. The player with the highest roll gets to go first, then play proceeds in whatever order, clockwise or counterclockwise, gets to the Game Master first. Characters can hold their actions to go later in the order, for example to run in a group together. Surprise Round If one group is surprised, then during their first turn they cannot do anything; but the other group cannot attack, they can only do things to build up advantage or move around. Alternatively, give the surprising group 2 advantage to represent their superiority. In Media Res If the player characters stumble into a group already actively doing something, the GM can award the NPC’s 1 to 3 advantage points to represent them preparing beforehand. Reactions Players have 2 actions per turn, but they can use one of their actions on someone else’s turn. The action cannot be casting a spell unless the spell has the “Reaction” modifier. The action has to be a direct response to the active character’s turn and target either the active character or their target. The Reaction cannot be the same action as the active character’s action. For example a character can try to attack someone running within their shunt and attack range, or try to grapple and body block someone who is attacking their friend within their reach.The person the character is responding to must either be in shunt range of the reacting character or be previously established to be the target of the reacting character. For example a character can whack someone running by them with a sword but they can only shoot someone with an arrow if they were aiming at them or the space they are running through the previous turn. If an action directly precludes another character’s action and the action has not been started yet, the active player can choose a different course of action, but if the action is fully or partially completed, then they stop where they are, and count as having used their action. If at all possible though, the active character will try to complete their action. For example, a character grabbed by someone while moving past will stop where they are and count as having moved, but a character attacked by someone will continue on their way where they wanted to move, and a character committed to attacking someone will continue to do so even if the character becomes magically shielded.When the reacting character’s turn comes around normally, they can only do one action instead of their normal 2. Naturally, this precludes them from doing things that take 2 actions like using charged up spells or running. A character with more than the normal 2 actions a turn can still only use one reaction, and a character with less than 2 actions a turn cannot take a reaction.
text.95: Before we go over the different types of actions, let’s go over what is not considered an action, and can be done for free during your turn. Usually these are things that take less than a few seconds, and can be done while doing something else. They might give you narrative permission to do something, but never Advantage Points. Here are the things that can be done for free during a turn: · Drawing a weapon or tool from your prepared belt with a free hand · Giving a quick shout out warning or command to another character (But not a long discussion) · Shunting over a meter or two (up to One Half Movement speed) when not running or sprinting · Flip a switch, draw a card or something similarly quick Improve situation The character does something cool to improve their situation - this can be throwing sand in the opponents eyes, ducking and weaving, swinging from the chandelier, etc. They describe their action and roll an appropriate skill against it. The character gains an advantage for attempting to do something cool and another advantage if they succeed. The roll is optional. Players can just take one advantage point for things like aiming if they can’t come up with something exciting. Improve situation is your #1 most used action. Generally speaking everything that does not get covered by an Attack or Move action is an Improve Situation action. Looking at that ancient statue? Better awareness of your environment. Stealing and eating a bread roll? The thrill and nutrition keep you in tip top shape. Giving off a satisfying one liner or communicating with your team during combat? Roll rapport for Improved Situation. Typically a skill roll can only be made once per scene unless the situation changes. Characters can’t keep rolling until they succeed, instead they have to find a different route to go through. Combat may be an exception to this, as the battlescape is constantly changing. Automatically improved situation Some positions automatically give you an advantage point which you can use to improve rolls. Don’t track these points - If the position changes you lose them. Instead your GM will tell you if any apply to a specific roll. Things like these can give you the advantage automatically:
text.107: Basic Rules A Social or Mental Attack can represent embarrassing the opponent, yelling at them and generally showing them up. This can be done to pressure people that normally you can’t physically hurt without serious repercussionsMental attacks have no range, but they must be witnessed by the target. Establish the Fiction The first thing to do is to figure out what’s happening in the fiction of the story - remember to think through the story before reaching for dice. Depending on what’s happening a social manipulation can be either an opposed roll or a roll versus the consider rating. Either way both parties will get advantage points based on the situation. Weight of Force If a character has an overwhelming advantage in power at the current time, such as being armed and armored or being known as a powerful wizard, they get an advantage. If the power is so disparate as to be obvious to everyone around, such as armored knights versus an unarmed man, they can get up to 2 advantage points. Weight of Numbers If a character is backed up by the majority of the characters in the scene, they get an advantage. If the advantage is greater than 3 on one, as a large gang on one man, they can get up to 2 advantage points. Weight of Society For every social strata difference between characters they get an advantage. Weight of Reason If the arguments the characters are making make sense they get an advantage. This is generally up to the Game Master, although the players can make arguments for why their ideas make sense for both parties. Strings Attached For every String they have on the other character they get an advantage.These advantage points are considered situational and go away after the check is made. Make the roll Roll vs consider or against a different skill, adding advantage as necessary. For consider this translates directly to a +2 to the target rating, while for an opposed roll it’s used as a normal point of advantage.If the character succeeds, their attempts to convince the target are successful, both logically and emotionally. The target believes the lie, is attracted to the character, thinks giving them a discount is a smart idea, etc. How they react is still up to the player.
text.130: If either side wins with an active roll, they can do one of the following to the other side: Deal Mental Damage When you deal Mind damage to a target, you are applying pressure to them, stressing them out and causing them to lose focus and concentration. They take Either 1d10+STR+INT Mind damage if the character is being threatening or 1d10+INT+EMP if the character is being more suave regardless of the skill rolled. Whichever number is rolled, If the target character does not believe that their life could be in danger, they only take half that damage. As is normal, the roll can be augmented by any leftover advantage points the character has. Gain a String A String is a permanent Advantage on a character forever; it can represent a piece of blackmail, a fond or embarrassing memory. Unlike a normal advantage, which is temporary, this is written down on your character sheet just like any other ability, power or item you have. Each subsequent time you use a social attack on the character you gain a free advantage as part of the roll. Outside of a social interaction, a character can use a String to gain an advantage on any other check, whether physically attacking, improving the situation or casting a spell. In that case they lose the String at the end of the scene. This is called Pulling a String. Make a Request Ask the character to do something, anything. Ultimately the narrative choice stays with the player for what the character will do, or is guided by the character’s disposition for the Game Master. Social interaction can be coercive but it is not mind control. The one making a request can offer to remove their own strings on the character as part of the request or give a material gift as part of the offer, and if the target still refuses they suffer one of the other consequences above. This represents the character making one of the choices less acceptable and more stressful for the target by portraying the request as a more attractive option. If the consequence for refusing the request is mind damage, the total value is rolled beforehand and used as a bargaining chip in the request.

text.174: Basic Rules Attacking Physically: Roll 2d10, choose lowest die and add your stats and skills compared to the opponent’s Dodge rating. If the attacker rolled above the Dodge rating of the defender, they hit the target. The body part they hit is determined by the number on their lowest die (Note that Advantage points can be used to reduce this number, but never raise it - only the total can be increased, not the rolled number) Head 1 Torso 2,3,4 Defensive (Shield) arm 5-6 Offensive (Primary) arm 7-8Off leg 9Fore leg 10 If you roll above the rating you do your weapon damage against them plus one die minus their armor for the body part. The damage can be taken by either the mind or the body at the defender’s choice, or split up as desired. If both your dice roll the same number and there’s no armor on the body part you also inflict a wound on that spot equal to the number on the die rolled. If there is a difference between the size of the creatures, add or subtract the difference to the roll. If the creature doesn’t take any damage, through Dodge, Armor or other means, they do not suffer the Wound. Worn armor can be sacrificed to reduce the incoming wound; instead the critical hit destroys the armor. Compare damage die roll to this chart 1 Stunned The target’s hit body part is damaged for d10 rounds 2 Sprained As above, and also the attacker gets to move the target up to half their move rating 3 Torn As above, but damaged until the character takes a Break 4 Ripped Muscle As above, and if the hit is to an arm the character drops what’s in their hands, and if is to the leg they fall prone 5 Broken As above, but damaged until the character Rests for a day 6 Gushing Blood As above, and the character gains the bleeding condition 7 Exposed Fracture As above, and the character’s wound will not heal without Recuperating 8 Extreme pain As above and deal damage to body and mind at the same time (potentially double damage) 9 Destroyed As above and body part permanently damaged 10 Cut off As above and body part missing

Note that if a character is asleep or restrained in such a way that they cannot dodge, the character’s dodge skill is reduced to 0 - you do not need to roll and can instead choose the body part you strike at. Roll one to confirm if you inflict a wound - if it lands on the same body part as you chose you do. Parrying & blocking If a character has an item in their hand and is hit in that arm, they can parry or block the blow. This only counts for the primary hand if the character has a two handed weapon. If they parry , they immediately roll a weapon skill versus the number rolled by their opponent. If they beat it, they take no damage and can counterattack with whatever is in their arm (if unspecified, the item does 1 Damage). If they block they gain an advantage and take no damage. Roll damage for the attacker. If the item’s structure is less than the attacker’s damage, it is destroyed. (if unspecified the item has 1 Structure) With a shield, the character can block incoming ranged attacks if they hit any part of the character covered by the shield. Active Dodging If a character is hit, they can actively dodge, spending Advantage points to increase their dodge score by +2 per point spent. A character cannot dodge with a damaged limb, or while wearing armor or holding equipment that they are not trained to use on that body part. A character can attack from up to 3 times that range with a disadvantage (-2 to the roll and advantage cannot be spent). Ranged attacks work the same as normal attacks with the following exceptions:
text.196: Basic Rules When a character attacks with their bare hands, they can do damage like they had a weapon, dealing d10+STR damage. There is no prerequisite skill for hand to hand combat. Unless you have at least one point in a hand to hand specialty you count as untrained. Because of the flexible and controllable nature of arms in hand to hand combat, attacking physically with your hands when trained counts as an improve situation roll as well as an attack. Untrained attack and Holding back A character who is untrained in a weapon, as represented by not having the prerequisite skill at the appropriate level) can only ever do half damage with that weapon, and cannot hold back their strength when attacking. On a critical hit, they take half of what they rolled for the effect.A character trained in using the weapon can choose to deal half damage by holding back (striking non vital areas, using the flat of the blade, etc) in an effort to keep their adversary alive. Note that this is not a fool-proof method of non-lethal combat; a hit to the back of the head can cause significant brain hemorrhage and an arrow to the knee can still cause a person permanent injury and death. If a player is interested in another character’s life or death, the Game Master can roll for it using the Dying rules in Advanced Rules section. Surrender: Characters that have an empathy score above 0 must fail an empathy check of 7 to attack a defenseless character. Defenselessness can mean knocked out, surrendered or unlikely to do harm. Interact Action As an action during their turn, the character can do anyhing not covered by the above three actions. These should not be overused, since most actions would improve a character’s situation, but if there’s no dramatic tension to an action, it doesn’t help anyone and it doesn’t attack anyone, it’s probably an Interact Action. An interact action should be something that takes a few seconds or more, otherwise it should be a Free action out of turn order.  Here’s a few examples of Interact Actions
text.201: As an action during their turn, the character can Move up to the character speed (5 meters + Dexterity/2) If both actions are used to move on a turn, the character can break into a Run to add (5 + Athletics:Run )meters per move to both moves. This is called your Run rating(Move + 5 + Athletics:Run) * 2. Having ran the previous turn, your character can sprint to move double your Run stat. This is not your character’s fasters possible speed (That would probably be handled by a Athletics:Run skill check), but it is the fastest speed they are comfortable at for some extended time. A character can jump as far as their Athletics - Jumping specialty roll would be or as high as your Athletics - Jump roll divided by 2 While moving through obstacles, the GM can ask for Skill checks to pass through certain obstacles, these are not considered improving your situation or taking an action by themselves, but can stop you or slow you down at the GM’s discretion. Difficult Terrain Whether crawling through a tight tunnel, treading through mud or pushing past dense underbrush, when a character moves through difficult terrain they can only move with one of their actions, and they cannot run. If they run into the difficult terrain their movement stops when they enter it. Especially difficult terrain that takes all your concentration, such as walking a tightrope or squeezing into a hole could take two actions to traverse. If you movement is disadvantaged in some way, such as an injured leg, you count all terrain as difficult terrain, and difficult terrain as especially difficult terrain Falling When falling from a great height, the character suffers 1d10 points of damage for every 3 meters they fall. This caps out at 100d10, at which point the character reaches terminal velocity. If falling into water, or into a steep angle that breaks the fall, cut the damage received in half.A character trained in falling can make a relevant roll versus the height of their fall to cut the damage in half.
text.205: Advanced Rules Magic runs in currents throughout the world - it is the arcane wizard’s plaything, the boon of a god or even the energy inside all living beings; it is power manifest and whatever its source - it is limited, dangerous and powerful. Spells are a declaration of magic and a description of their gameplay effects. A spell is made of powers and modifiers, and has a spell power and mental cost. The spell power represents the chance of the spell failing, while the mental cost represents how tired a character would get after casting such a spell. There are two primary ways of casting magic: by preparing or casting it. Those who prepare spells do so before they activate the spell, expending money and time in exchange for not having to risk failure in the heat of the moment, conjuring potions and magical objects to do the casting for them. Casters meanwhile control the flow of magic in the moment the spell is cast, paying a mental toll for their effort, but having the ability to cast more powerful magic than a prepared caster would be able to. Winds of Chaos: Chaos is a fickle and powerful thing, and pulling on the thread of one magical line has the capacity to bring the whole structure of creation down on the one who deigned to pull on it. Every  place and time has a different difficulty for magic, represented as a number 1 through 10. When the first spell is cast in a scene or someone tests the winds of magic, the GM rolls a d10 (or makes up a number if it’s important to the plot). When someone casts a spell they must make a skill check using their casting specialty and beat the chaos  number added to the Spell Point rating of the spell. The winds of magic can be disturbed by any character First the caster must pay the cost of the spell - if they can’t afford the cost of the spell they can’t start it.The caster can choose to pay the cost from their pool of Arcane points or Mind points, or split it up as desired. Casting of the spell To manifest the results of the spell, the caster rolls a skill check adding their spell casting specialty and any bonuses versus the spell difficulty and winds of chaos numbers added together.

If rolling a 10 would not have allowed the caster to cast the spell and they fail to cast the spell, the spell does not activate, even on a critical roll result. Magic Mishaps Magic is a fickle thing, and controlling the pathways of chaos is fraught with danger for the caster and those around them. When failing to cast a spell or rolling a critical result, the spell goes awry. At the GM’s discretion the spell can expierience any of the effects of the below table, or the effect of the lower die the caster rolled. In case of a critical success, this happens together with the spell casting. 1The spell fizzles - it simply doesn’t happen or doesn’t affect the characters. 2Wrong target - the target is chosen by a different player (usually the GM), and can be in secret. For example, a portal can open to the wrong spot, or a fireball can target a different character 3Wrong effect - Fire freezes, Granite boils, Ice burns and pain becomes laughter and healing rends flesh apart - the new effect is made up by a different player (usually the GM) 4Lingering Magic - an identical spell is cast next turn, with Mishap #2 Wrong Target 5Magic feedback - The caster takes a point of Exhaustion 6Winds of Magic Change - re roll the Winds of Magic, the new result stays 7Space Rift - The caster and anyone around them are moved 5m in the opposite direction of the target of the spell and knocked prone 8Terrible Visions - Chills and fear, and secret heat - The caster takes a point of Madness as they gaze past the abyss 9Malevolent Energies - the spell deals extra d10 damage to the target (if the caster is a creature) or the caster (caster chooses) in addition to other effects . Since no dice are rolled in the casting of these spells, they can neither gain the user Mind points nor cause them damage. Improvised Magic Magic is a chaotic and dangerous force, and should not be tampered with lightly. Usually spells are structured with specific powers covered in the Magic chapter, but smaller scale spells can be performed on the fly by manipulating the magical currents all around us without too much fear. If a character has a Magical specialty and would be able to do something by mundane means but wishes to use magic to achieve the same ends for flavor, they can roll their skill and specialty like normal and sacrifice 1 Mind point to narrate the action as magical. text.220: Advanced Rules Fire If a character passes through locations that are on fire, they roll a Dexterity skill check with a difficulty of 7 plus the number of body parts in contact with the fire. If they fail the check, they add Burning Condition to their character, which damages them by d10 points per round until they put themselves out. If they are in a confined space where all the air is replaced with smoke, they might also start taking damage from the Suffocating Condition. Water Characters can swim in the water at Mobility - Swim speed, and can breathe underwater for Travel - Survival or Half their Physique - Endurance minutes (whichever is higher). After that, they gain the Suffocating condition, which damages them by d10 points per round. Exhaustion Being excessively Tired, whether from lack of Sleep, Food or other grueling tasks can impose a condition known as Exhaustion. Being Mentally broken and traveling at a breakneck pace gives exhaustion. Cold, Heat, Starvation all give a point of Exhaustion per day. When a character is exhausted, they Subtract a point from Dodge, Perception, Consider (to a minimum of 1) and any skill checks the character makes for every point of Exhaustion they have. For Example, a character with 3 points of exhaustion who got a 5 on their Travel check would instead act as if they got a 2. text.247: Grievous Injury A character who loses a limb through combat or other gruesome happenstance (always a critical failure result, but it can happen from anything that deals damage, falling rocks, a fire, spell going out of control, etc) is in a world of trouble. A lost limb is not necessarily the end of a character’s career, but it’s a problem they will need to deal with in short order. Different limbs affect different abilities of the character. ·    Arms - Disadvantage on Dexterity rolls·    Body - Disadvantage on Strength rolls ·    Head - Disadvantage on Empathy, Intelligence rolls·    Legs - Disadvantage on any Movement rolls and Immobilized condition (no sprinting) We don’t have to cover permanent damage to the body or head because the destruction of those organs leads to instant death, but for the arms and legs there are three degrees of damage; ·    A damaged limb is one that will come back to normal status in a while - it carries a disadvantage -2 to rolls depending on the body part·    A destroyed limb is one that is useless, either paralyzed, damaged or so weak as to not be useful. It carries a disadvantage of -2 to the limb·    A missing limb is one that got cut, burned or ripped off - it carries an extreme disadvantage of -4 to the appropriate Skills rolls, and Immobilized II for legs (no sprinting or running) Disadvantages and conditions stack for multiple limbs missing, so a character missing one leg and with a destroyed other can only move for 1 action out of their turn.Characters  can attempt to mitigate a wound, either with magic or a prosthetic. Magic carries some potential dangers and requires the use of a spellcaster, which may not come cheap. ·    A peg leg or hook made of cheap materials is a small item and changes a -4 extreme disadvantage to a -2 disadvantage·    A Quality prosthetic can require hand crafting an item and cost 100 denar and removes the disadvantage, although it still applies a -2 modifier to rolls.·    A magical prosthetic can be obtained for 2000 Denars that completely removes the disadvantage from a Runesmith of Nature (wood), Sorcery (brass or metal) or Necrotic (bone) disciplines  (Counts as a Rune of SP 4 Animate Materials 1, Geas[Act like missing limb])
text.248: Advanced Rules Mounts: Riding another character - The other character must be agreeable and 1 size larger than you. To mount is an improve situation action with Animal handling - Riding vs DC 7 while to mount a disagreeable character is an attack against their mental points using your Animal Handling - Tame skill vs the character’s Dodge. While riding, both the rider and mount act at the same time. The player controlling them gets 3 actions to spend between them, making sure that neither party gets more than 2 a turn. One extra action is added per extra rider. Bipedal Creatures are difficult to mount, and provide a disadvantage to the rider on any action they take unless a special harness is produced. In situations where there are multiple players in one mount/rider combo, they have to determine who is in control of the third action; if they cannot agree, both can only take one action that turn as they argue with each other, whether verbally or otherwise. If the rider falls to 0 Mind points, they can only take one action, as their other one is preoccupied with not falling off the mount. If a mount falls unconscious, the character on top is thrown onto the ground. Roll 2d10. The smaller one indicates the body part you land on while the larger one + your steed’s size is the damage you take. Y ou also drop anything in your hands. Critical hits occur as normal on matched dice.This damage doesn’t occur if the rider gets off the mount on their own turn or is pushed off the steed in some way, only if the mount dies underneath them. An attacker can choose to target the rider or mount. The rider adds the Mount’s Dodge to theirs if chosen.The mount adds the rider’s Consider to theirs if chosen.The mount is the only character who can move out of the two. Animals cannot make Dexterity or Intelligence based skill rolls unless they have a point in that skill. The only exception is if someone makes an Animal handling - Handle skill check to instruct them to do so. This check is done against the animals consider rating and then the animal has to actually make the skill check.
text.251: Advanced Rules Conditions represent any long lasting effects or dangers a character might face, such as being set on fire, poisoned, thrown or grappled. Conditions are made of three parts: · Effect - what happens to you when the condition is resolved · Resolve Time - how often the condition is resolved · Stop point - how this condition ends Conditions can also have an intensity, which will amplify their effects. Condition Effects Condition effects can be modified by the Game Master as desired, but here are some common ones: Damaging conditions: Roll a d10 equal to the intensity and reduce either Mind or Body by the highest number rolled. When under the effect of multiple damaging conditions, roll the number of dice for all conditions at once and choose the single highest die, do not add the damage together. For example, someone who is bleeding heavily (2 dice) and on fire (1 dice) would roll 3 d10 and choose the highest one, reducing their mind and or body by the number rolled. If multiple dice roll the same number, add that number to the total damage dealt, and if the number rolled is under a 5  it counts as a critical wound. For example, someone who is Covered in flames burning (5 dice) rolls 10, 7, 8, 7, 2, they would take 17 damage (10+7) Exhaustion conditions Increase or Reduce max mind or body by the condition intensity per point per time increment. When this condition ends, their maximum mind and body points restore to what they had before. When under the effect of multiple withering conditions, reduce the max mind or body by their combined Intensity Action Economy condition Reduce number of actions by 1 or 2 or increase by 1 Action economy conditions do not stack, increase or reduce the number of actions by the highest condition intensity. Two opposite action economy conditions cancel each other out. Immobilized condition Cannot sprint, cannot run, cannot move for 1 or 2 of the actionsImmobilized conditions can stack, reduce the number of available move actions by the highest condition
text.268: Advanced Rules Money comes in Gold Solidus (Solid Gold Coin worth 1 Gold) Gold Aureus (Partial Gold coin worth 1/20th of a Solidus) of Silver Denarius (Silver coin worth 1/100th the Aueres) and the Copper Assess (copper coin worth 1/10 the Denarius) Worth in Solid Gold: Gold Solidus: 1 Gold Aureus: .05 Silver Denarius: .0005 Copper Assess: .00005 Worth in Gilded Aureus: Gold Solidus: 20 Gold Aureus: 1 Silver Denarius: 1% Copper Assess: .001 Worth in Silver Denars: Gold Solidus: 2000 Gold Aureus: 100 Silver Denarius: 1 Copper Assess: 1/10 Worth in Copper Assess: Gold Solidus: 20000 Gold Aureus: 1000 Silver Denarius: 10 Copper Assess: 1 Lifestyle expenses determine your social status. Y ou have to spend this amount to have this social status. If you can’t afford the cost of being a beggar, you start starving to death and expire in 2 months. Some groups prefer counting every penny. If you do so, the characters must buy enough things per day in order to remain in their social class. Otherwise, you can skip over any minor purchase as long as it is in the character’s means and just deduct a lump sum at the beginning of the day. If the character desires to live beyond their means, they can still pay the appropriate price for that one off item. Minor purchase is defined as anything up to ¼ of your daily spending, so for a rich man or emperor can be quite substantial! Characters have to spend their living expenses, but that money doesn’t just disappear. For poorer lifestyles it covers their shelter and food, but for more expensive lifestyles this includes servants, mercenaries and travel arrangements. A single expenditure of money can cover several character’s lifestyles, a Rich character can pay for a Middle class one, who in turn pays for a Peasant, etc.
text.269: The world of Mortal Reins is built on a stratified state of money and power, where those terms are roughly interchangeable; and those with money get quickly surrounded by sycophants and hangers on trying to get a slice of the pie, all the way up to the emperors of the world. For a system that is so class-conscious, society is surprisingly pliable and meritorious. There is no reverence to ancient bloodlines or established kingdoms, only money and power; items that change hands daily. To increase your social strata, a character must · Have the lodging of the appropriate social class (see Equipment chapter) · Spend at least the daily upkeep amount on lifestyle, leisure and lodging per day for a period of multiple days. · Look the part in terms of clothing, jewelry and equipment. Once they’ve done so, they move up to the next social tier. This can happen without the player’s express desire - if the game master notices they’ve been spending a lot of money on private rooms, baths and clothing as a lower strata player they can automatically bump them up to the next layer. Losing your social strata happens when you · Go traveling without enough supplies to carry on the lifestyle. · Can’t afford or don’t want to pay the daily upkeep for a few days · Lose their access to lodging, servants or resources When you change your social strata, 4 things change:Y our Consider Rating increases by 1 point per Social Strata as you stop caring about other peopleY ou get an additional advantage point when interacting with those below you in social class.From Peasant to Middle Class, your Maximum Body points increase as you improve your daily nutrition and get proper rest and exercise From Rich to Emperor Class, your Mind increases as you have enough time to study and meditate, giving you extra Mind points · Peasant class upkeep gives you nutrition and exercise, making your base Body to 12 · Middle class upkeep gives you even more nutrition, allowing your base Body to become 14 · Being Rich allows you to make use of the majority of your time studying, meditating or leisure, allowing a Body of 14 and Mind of 12
text.277: Advanced Rules Characters can rest for a day or vacation for a few days. Resting for a day requires roughly the day’s worth of expenses as they pay for living, food etc. Even if they’re camping in the wilderness they must have prepared for themselves expenses to keep their social strata. Characters can take a break for an hour. They must describe an activity they do for an hour to relax and negotiate a relevant skill with the GM and difficulty to do it in the current situation (much harder to write some poetry when you’re hanging off the back of a titan hurtling at inhuman speed through the void). If they succeed they regain as many Mind points as they rolled on the higher die. If they fail they regain as many Mind points as was on the lower die. In either case they gain back 1 Body point. A character can take a break once every quarter of a day or when they hit 0 Mind points. Characters that rest for a day gain back all their Mind points and Roll a check for Physique - Rest versus how restful the GM describes their rest as. If they succeed they regain as much Body as on the higher die. If they fail, as much as on the lower. Either way multiply the amount of body points gained back by their size rating. They can also perform any class specific rest abilities, such as crafting items for an alchemist or praying for a Priest. If they rest for a full day they also get an advantage for being well rested for their next scene. A character can take a rest once a day. Characters can also recuperate for 3 days. If they do so they gain back all hit points, body and mind. They heal all non-permanent injuries. They are also assumed to have the ability to go shopping for items, as limited by the GM. They also get an advantage for being well rested for their next scene.Takes 1 hour of restful activityCan be done every 6 hours or at 0 MindHeal 1 BodyHeal d10 MindHeal Wounds of severity 3 and belowSorcerers get half Arcana backPriests get half Arcana back OR can change their Active SpellsWarlocks can change their Active Spells
text.280: by strenuous activity, the characters can act as if they’ve taken the previous level of rest. Working for 30 hours without taking a single rest (skipping a night of sleep) adds a point of Exhaustion (-1 Dodge, Consider, Perception and all skill rolls), which accumulates for every night skipped in this way. In addition, if the character is in extreme cold or heat they gain another point of Exhaustion and if they are wet they gain another point of Exhaustion per day. Restful Activity Resting does not mean a character is knocked out and unresponsive. The player can continue roleplaying during the downtime they get as their character.While resting you can socialize, make plans, walk at a leisurely pace, shop for items, send letters and anything else that doesn’t require intense focus or physical exertion. If someone makes a social attack against a character, they can choose to accept the terms of the social attack or count their rest as interrupted.If someone makes a physical attack against a  character, their rest is automatically interrupted. Profits Adventuring is dangerous and nobody would do it if it wasn’t also quite profitable. The following table is a guideline for how much a customer should be willing to pay out for a group of adventurers to go on a quest for them if he hopes to be able to hire them. Of course it’s nothing but a guideline - the actual negotiations can include myriads of factors that can lead to a different price such as how much a person likes them, the supply of people willing to do a job, whether the payment is up front or at the end, how desperate the buyer is.. If there’s nobody with the cash to hire someone rich in town, it may well end up that the rich adventurer will end up with no job! The rows represent the company’s social class and the columns how dangerous the buyer expects the job to be from a basic job to them expecting none of the party to survive (and therefore not too worried about paying them later), in terms of payment for 1 day for 1 person.
text.293: Advanced Rules Traveling Often, characters will need to get from one place to another. If nothing exciting happens during that journey, feel free to narratively skip over the entire trip - but the travel will still consume resources - chiefly time and supplies. Time to Travel Hiking pace: This is the pace of generally walking forward without exerting too much effort. Note that this is still tiring, even exhausting over long hours, just not enough to damage your body. A character can more at their Move speed * km per hour or Move speed * 5 km per day . A party that travels together does so at the pace of their slowest member. Heavy Goods: A character carrying over their carry limit cuts their hiking pace to Move speed * 4km ; A character over Encumbered cuts their hiking pace to Move speed * 3km ; and a character over that limit decreases their hike pace by Move speed * 1km per level of over encumbrance Forced March pace: A character can walk for longer than 10 hours in a day, or faster than is comfortable for them - for every subsequent increment of Move Speed * 5 km that the character travels in a day without rest they take the highest of a number of d10 equal to the distance already traveled points of Mind Damage and 1 Point of Exhaustion . At the end of their journey for the day, they make a Physique - Endurance check with a difficulty equal to the Mind damage taken in the day. If they fail the Endurance check, they take Body Damage equal to the Mind Damage taken, and double the amount of Exhaustion . If they are Encumbered, they have a disadvantage on this check. If the character fails, they can choose to take the full body damage and show up at the destination or give up halfway through and take half body damage. Example: Touzrek has a move speed of 6, and is faster by exerting yourself. Difficult Terrain All these times assume the best possible conditions and fastest times a character will move. At the GM’s discretion due to terrain, weather or any other number of conditions the pace might be cut in half or even halted entirely.
text.309: lodging of appropriate quality - something that is more difficult in the woods than in a town with shops and inns! Characters can either pre purchase these traveling supplies or by acquiring them on the road with a Travel - Scavenger or Resource - Supplies roll. · A Vagabond has to use a Scavenge roll, and cannot use a Supplies roll · a Rich man or Emperor has to use Resource, and cannot scavenge for servants. · To use Resource in this manner requires paying the associated daily fee as if you used it to obtain a common item in a flashback. · Once you fail on a Resource - Supplies roll, you cannot use it again until you have reached a city that could feasibly sell food and other supplies. Y ou’ve run out of supplies. If a character has pre-purchased supplies, they do not need to start rolling until they’re burned through their purchased supplies. Starvation If you fail even the vagabond level difficulty, your character begins to starve. Take a point of Exhaustion If you fail the vagabond scavenge roll by 5 or more, you are unable to find water, and must take d10 points of Exhaustion. When you first get food and water, roll Physique - Endurance and heal as much Exhaustion as you roll. Repeat this every time you take a rest with food and water until you reach 0 Exhaustion. Ultimately the difficulty of these rolls are up to the GM, but some suggestions are listed below. text.312: Advanced Rules There are many maladies ready to pounce on unsuspecting adventurers, lords and serfs alike. Aside from external injury, the body is full of internal ills that can be spread by a scratch or cut. Many common ailments have been discovered over time, but some are still mysteries to this day. Infection When a character is finished resting and they have more than 5 points of body lost, they must make a check against infection with a difficulty equal to their missing body points.Alternatively, if they are resting and have a wound, make a check against infection with a difficulty equal to the wound injury severity. The infection check is Physique - Constitution or Lore - Medicine; a Medicine check can be done by another person, but a Constitution check needs to be made by the infected character. The Constitution check is made with Disadvantage if the character lost body points from a bite previously or is in unsanitary conditions (swamps, ghettos).The Medicine check is made with a Disadvantage per extra person that the medic treats at once. If the players remember the body part that was struck when the character lost body points, that part gets infected. Otherwise, roll a d10 and choose a random part. Y ou get the first tier of Infection. Progression Head Body Arms Legs Infected -2 Maximum Mind, -2 Maximum Body Fever -1d10 Maximum Mind points Chills -1d10 Maximum Body points NerveDamageDisadvantage EMP , INTSluggish-1 ActionDisadvantage DEX, STRImmobilized-1 Move Action Spread The disease progresses to another body part. Roll a d10. Progression: Once a day or every long rest the character must make a Physique - Constitution skill check: Beating a roll of 12 means the character adds a tally next to their infection and are once step closer to curing it!Failing to beat a difficulty of 7 means the disease progresses one step. The effects of the disease progressing are communal, additive, so  you lose extra points on top of the points already lost so far. Treatment:
text.320: Advanced Rules Corruption and Madness The loss of purity and sanity is often the result of a curse or spell gone awry, but it could happen to even the most stalwart souls when exposed to the evils of an uncaring world. This corruption can take many forms: For example, an adventurer might lose his sense of smell, so that he cannot recognize danger. Or a nobleman might forget all of his friends and family, leaving him completely alone in the world. Usually this fit passes, but the choices characters make in their insanity stay with them their whole life. When people witness things that could drive a normal person insane, such as: ·    Direct Interference of an extra-planar god·    Exuberant, excessive blood and gore (being ripped apart piece by piece, slowly being eaten alive, etc) ·    Mental or sexual violence done against them or their loved ones ·    Being forced to do something traumatizing against their will The characters must succeed on a check against a difficulty set by the GM using their Empathy - Willpower - Self Control specialty or take a point of madness. Losing hold of Reality Whenever a character takes a point of Madness or completes a Long Rest (one day of rest)The GM rolls in secret on the Insanity table, making a note of the result without revealing it to the player. To roll on the table, the GM rolls d10 and adds the number of Madness points the character has. When the effect activation becomes relevant, the GM shifts their narration with the effects of madness in mind or takes control of the character to perform the actions specified the same way as if the character was under the effects of Mind Control. Rest & Treatment Self Medication It’s quite possible the characters will not have time to go on a prolonged retreat to cure their madness until their adventure is complete. On a shorter scale, characters can deal with their issues by partaking in various vices to suppress the issue. Depending on their situation, they can expend some money and roll a specialty describing how they indulge in their vice: whether that be drugs, violence, sex, drinking, gambling or something else. Roll with disadvantage DC10+your madness points check. The difficulty can be adjusted by the GM depending on the availability of resources to partake in. On a crit or failure the character overindulges, losing time, money, mind, body or reputation, and immediately rolling on the insanity table and triggering the effect. If you fail, you get as many days reprieve from madness as you rolled in the tens digit, if you succeed you get double that, and any currently untriggered Madness Breaks are removed.
