text.351: Advanced Rules Characters who are grievously injured or who have fulfilled their dream are retired. They must choose a social strata at or below their current style of living for which they satisfy at least a month’s worth of expenses. If they can satisfy 10 year’s worth of expenses for that strata, they can live off their savings, and need not work as they pursue their passions outside of adventuring. If not, they must work. Choose an appropriate profession for that strata and roll a test determined by the GM. Various factors can give advantage to that roll, primarily other financial benefactors or people dedicated to the person’s well-being. Divide the number you roll by 2 and that gives you the number of months you can cover with working. If you now have a year’s worth of living expenses, you are able to survive at that strata. If not, check if you satisfy any lower strata. If not that, your character dies of sickness, starvation and general malady. Separate from the money, roll Rapport (Fame) and add the number of significant individuals you personally helped as well as any family members you have. Add 10 if you have achieved your dream. 0-10 10-20 20-100 100-500 500+ Y ou die alone in obscurityY ou die surrounded by friends and familyY ou are locally known and fondly remembered Y ou probably are in a book somewhere, at least until it is burned or crumbles awayY our name is known across the world, at least for a little time Finally, narrate what happens to your character after they retire.For Inspiration, roll 3 dice on the table below. Each dice has to do with a question, and is up to the players to interpret. The questions are:What will help you / What will hinder you / What is your unrealized potential The GM reserves the right to bring your character back as an NPC during their journey to the abyss. The Tower Crumbles - destruction; everything is ruined; the worst outcome you can think of comes to pass. The upheaval is collective and impersonal, it doesn’t just affect the character but everyone around them.
text.388: At 0 body points, a character is physically broken, and can no longer perform any actions. They can crawl in place, collect their innards, beg for their mother or just be knocked out. They instantly lose any Advantage points they had. If an enemy attack takes the character to 0 or negative body points, they also suffer a Dying condition. Characters’ body points can become negative if they suffer more damage than their body points total. Starting their next turn and every turn until their character stabilizes, a character who is bleeding out but not dead yet makes a Strength roll with a difficulty equal to how many body points in the negative they are. This is the only thing they can do during that turn, once per turn. · Once a character achieves two successes, the Dying condition stops, they are stabilized and will regain consciousness when their body and mind are above 0, unless under the effects of other conditions. · On a failure, they get another Dying condition intensity, and immediately roll their damage from all damaging conditions, and they get 1 advantage point. · On a critical roll, regardless of success or failure, you also get 2 advantage points and don’t need to take your Condition damage for the round If a character has a different condition, such as bleeding, being poisoned or on fire, they cannot stabilize that on their own, and someone has to help them. Any attack on a stable unconscious character immediately destabilizes them if they are not killed by it. A character who is healed to positive body points is automatically stabilized, as long as they are not under the effect of some other damaging condition, such as fire, drowning or poison. Once a character reaches negative body points equal to their negative body total they die. Medicine rolls and Healing magic no longer affect the dead character, they must get their soul back with the resurrection power. Strands of Fate: Characters have fate points that represent their ability to evade certain death. Fate can be used to counteract death, instead taking you to exactly your negative body point total but leaving you stable. Y ou will wake up with a scar just like if you stabilized at the very last second, your conditions will end and your enemies will leave you for dead.Beware! Some encounters can kill your character more than once. For example, if a troll beats a character to death, they might be taken, stripped and eaten afterwards, or perhaps antagonists particularly angry at the character keep stabbing them after they expire. Generally, these cannot be salvaged by spending a fate point:
text.393: Dying If your character reaches negative their body point total they are dead. This can be achieved from a single large hit, bleeding out or an attack after you have already been reduced to 0 body points. For every day afterwards you lose 10 body points. 24-72 hours after death — the internal organs decompose. 3-5 days after death — the body starts to bloat and blood-containing foam leaks from the mouth and nose. 8-10 days after death — the body turns from green to red as the blood decomposes and the organs in the abdomen accumulate gas. After death, your soul floats around the place it was killed for a month. During this time, and in possession of a relatively undamaged or patched up body a proper spell can bring a character back to life. The body must be brought back to 0 Health and the soul brought back to it. It’s quite possible that resurrection will not be possible for your character and instead your story will end here. Let the other players resolve the current scene and then play out your eulogy. Each other surviving character mentions one thing they liked about your character and the way they grieve. Then, roll Rapport (Fame), multiply that by 10 and add the number of significant individuals you personally helped as well as any family members you have. Subtract 10 if your body was not recovered and brought to civilization. Add 10 if you have achieved your dream. 0-10 10-20 20-100 100-500 500+ No funeral is held for you. Perhaps a few people grieve alone and in silence.Y our friends and family arrive at your funeral, a private event to celebrate your life.Y ou are locally known and fondly remembered. A poem is written about you.Y ou probably are in a book somewhere, and mentioned in some more obscure songsY our name is known across the world, at least for a little time. Finally, narrate what happens to your character’s estate after they die - Including what is written in your will and how any dependents you had react. text.395: Character Creation One is the narrative component of a character, and the other is the numbers and powers that describe their ability to affect the outside world. Both are equally important for the game. Role playing is a conversational game, so without the structure of the rules and numbers for the character we wouldn’t be able to properly gauge the outcome of an action, or create the dramatic tension that comes with the possibility of failure. The narrative half however, is equally important as without it the player might struggle deciding what their character’s priorities are and how they could be a driving protagonist in the world the other players weave with them. A character without the statistics is an idea, and a character without a story remains a set of numbers on a paper. While making the character, you can start with either part, having a concrete idea that you build the statistics around or rolling and creating the statistics before deciding what kind of story they would build or you can do both at the same time and have one organically inform and affect the other. This chapter assumes you’ll do it the second way, having only a vague idea of the character and coming up with more details about their outlook on and role in life as you come up with the abilities and skills of the character. It will go over each step in the following order: Getting the four core statistics of your character - Strength, Dexterity, Intellect and Empathy Picking a starting origin and character race, choosing your initial skills and languages Creating your Character’s Personality, Motivation, Dream and Conflict Choosing a profession for your character to take skills, specialties and abilities from Choosing a social strata for your character, which determines how much they pay for upkeep and how much they are respected by their peers Picking up initial equipment for your character either by choosing a starting set of items or For each of your four statistics(Strength, Dexterity, Intelligence, Empathy), roll 3 ten sided dice,
text.409: Character Creation Choose a Race, Place of Origin and Name Look at the races available and choose one to play as. It will have special features and languages, as well as potential places you would be from. It also has a series of skills you would have picked up as you grew up, or would have an easier time grasping with your natural advantages. Spend 5 XP between your racial skills and mark that you are proficient in them, just like if you have just gotten 5 XP through adventuring. These XP do not count towards the total XP in your profession. Y ou can also grasp an extra language for 1 XP in lieu of a skill Races Races change the maximum cap of all attributes from 10 to 10 + their respective bonuses. The minimum cap of all stats remains 1. Races also come with a starting skills choice - These represent the skills you may have come across during your early life. Any skills that you take at least 1 point in from your race you gain proficiency in, meaning you can then spend XP to further upgrade them even if it is not in your current professionOn Language - There is no Common Language In many games or stories, there is a language known by all the characters and all cultures; but that is a gross oversimplification of life. Each of the groups in Mortal Reins has a language assosiated with them, and people’s language informs and is informed by their culture, society and way of life (For more of this - see the Living in the world chapter)There is often a Common Language of the Land, but that language may be different depending on which Land the story takes place in, and should be agreed on by all players.  Characters without a language in common can still interact as long as the concepts they throw around are simple enough, and its assumed even if the players are talking that the characters are using a few of the words they’ve picked up, hand gestures and body language to convey their meaning; sometimes it’s fun for a player to lean into the language barrier, but if the player doesn’t want to, they can say the character is conveying the meaning, although with some struggles.
text.416: Character Creation Some of the most industrious people around the middle sea are the dwarves. They toil in the land and under mountains, creating awe inspiring architecture and wondrous tools. Their holds are the envy of many, and often they are ransacked by invaders and monsters. Appearance A dwarf is both shorter and more stout than a human, at  4’(120cm) - 5’(150cm) in height and weighing around 70 to 100 kg. Almost all of the males have a full beard, and it is considered a mark of dishonor or exile to shave it off. The females sometimes shave their beard, especially if they live in a mixed race community, but this is looked down on by more conservative dwarves, and the women who want a position of power under the mountain grow out magnificent beards just like the men. Dwarf skin is usually white and even a little pale owing to the amount of time they spend underground, although their propensity to burn in the sun easily lends their cheeks and forehead a reddish color. Age A standard dwafor comes of age at 50 years old, after having spent 40 years in education and training. They live to be up to 3 centuries old, after which the combined grumpiness overpowers their will to live, and many older dwarves will stop frivolous distractions like food and sleep to focus on their magnum opus. Views on Other Races Dwafor enjoy the passions of humans who Dwafor characters increase their Strength statistic by 1 point at character creation. When selecting this race, choose if you are a Mountain or Hill Dwarf. Mountain Dwarves increase Intelligence by 1 Hill Dwarves increase Empathy by 1 Skills Dwafor are able to select from the following skills during their early upbringing: · Smash · Launch· Craft· Resourcefulness· Reasoning· Lore · Willpower· Physique Mountain Dwarves are also able to select: · Mysticism And Hill Dwarves are also able to select: · Rapport Special Abilities Stout Legs: Dwafor increase their movement speed by 1m per move action. [Move = DEX/2 + 6] But they do not add 10 from their run speed [Run = Move*2 +Athletics: Run*2]. When doing a forced march, the Dwarf has a disadvantage to their Physique checks.
text.423: Character Creation The fair folk used to be the undisputed masters of the continent in the first age of magic and bronze, but in the last millennia they have been outpaced by the younger races and relegated to living in hiding, crushed between mighty empires and kingdoms. In this they are aided by their natural skill with magic and athleticism. Appearance Outwardly, elves look a lot like humans, maybe only slightly shorter on average. Their ears are sharper than a humans, and their skin, although in similar tones as a humans, never has any blemishes nor marks. They stand between 5’ (152cm) to 5’10” (178cm) tall, but weight significantly less than an equivalently sized man, often less than 40kg Age Aelfor are immortal, and old age does not cause them frailty or death the way it does the other races. On average though, an elf will only live to 500 years before they are claimed by violence, sickness or some other statistic. Elves decide themselves when they have come of age, with some claiming adulthood as early as at 30, while others enjoying their childhood deep into their second century. Views on Other Races The longevity of the elves leads them to a Aelfor characters increase their Dexterity and Intelligence statistics by 1 point at character creation. Skills Aelfor are able to select from the following skills during their early upbringing: · Accuracy· Launch· Mobility · Deceive· Athletics· Animal Handling · Notice· Stealth · Travel· Thievery Special Abilities Natural Illusionists: Aelfor have innate magical powers, even if they do not attune to them. At character creation, an aelfor can create three spells or choose 3 from the list below. An elf power is a stable spell of illusion magic of up to 9 Spell points. An elf can use one of their Natural Illusion Powers one time anytime. Using the elf power takes an action, but no roll needs to be made. When the aelfor rests for 12 hours or more, their power recharges. Eagle eye The elf gets +4 Notice for this turn. Camouflage
text.437: Character Creation same ancient race which presided over the world 10 thousand years ago. When the younger races of the second age started reclaiming what was left of the world, the Aelimfor fortified their island fortresses. Instead of going into hiding like the majority of the elves, they continue their stewardship of the world, influencing the decisions of leaders and major events from the shadows using their agents and diplomats. Appearance The Aelimfor have a lithe build similar to a normal elves, but are considerably taller, between 5’10 (178cm) to 6’10” (208cm). They weight as much as an elf of similar size, that is half of what a human would weigh. Their skin tone looks like an elves with all the blood drained from it - many of the elves are pale, tinted with blue or green, although some have darker skin. Age As all elves, the Aelimfor are functionally immortal, and their lifestyle allows for statistically longer lifespans of 6 or 7 centuries. The older the elf is the more cavalier they become with their life, and more willing they are to take chances which eventually result in their doom. Views on Other Races Aelimfor were slow to react to the rise of the Empathy statistics by 1 point at character creation. With the ending of the war they have slowly evolved to have slightly longer lifespans, with some urks living up to 50 or 80 years old. Views on Other Races Burn short but bright are words the orcs live by. Having a limited lifespan, they strive to build a lasting legacy for themselves, through their works or their clan. text.461: Character Creation The kaskine cat people are one of the youngest sentient races to join the middle sea. They come from the jungles and deserts of the south in a great migration northwards, although not many like to talk about why they left their ancestral homeland. Their cultural insularity and secretiveness has not earned them many friends. Appearance They are of a similar height and build as a human, although their legs have a pronounced double jointed bend - kaskine walk on their toes, which are often as large as a whole human foot. They are covered in short furs of different colors, usually grey black or orange and have cat-like tails, ears and faces. Age A kaskine can live anywhere between 50 to 100 years old. Between the years of 20 and 40 they are expected to go on a Sionao - a form of pilgrimage as a rite of passage where they must leave their tribe or village and make something of themselves. Being fiercely individualistic, the Sionao is often used by the elder members of the tribe to exile those they clash with, or just plain dislike. Views on Other Races The kaskine are natural born travelers and traders, and are good with money. This has led to them having a reputation as schemers and deceivers, but that reputation is mostly unfounded. Preferring freedom of movement, the Kaskine dislike the insular Dwarves and conversely like the always friendly Humans, but their hatred is reserved for Skeox rats and Vaurl beastmen, who they have sometimes been conflated with by the other races. Special Abilities High Jump Kaskine are able to jump twice as high and far as any other race. Low Light Vision As long as any light is present, the Kaskine can see as in daylight, provided they have a minute to adjust their vision to the ambient light. They cannot see in total darkness though, requiring changes at character creation: · +2 Dexterity · +1 Intelligence Skills Kaskine are able to select from the following skills during their early upbringing: · Stealth · Rapport · Resourcefulness
text.464: Character Creation race, and the only one to truly come from the middle sea. Even the elves with their timeless memories struggle to remember when the Xoglio first appeared, although some theorized it was right at the end of the first age, when a mysterious sea peoples invaded many coastal countries. Xoglio can live in the ocean but they prefer fresh water, living in ponds, swamps and rivers throughout the empire. Appearance The Xoglio are lizard-like in nature, although they stand on two feet. They are heftier than a man, maybe twice as large in weight. Their scales often have bright colors, cyan, green and orange being some among many. Inside their race there are large differences between individuals, from crests to sacks to different types of eyes and tongues. Age A Xoglio is born from a clutch of eggs in a nursery together with its many brethren, although only a few will survive to adulthood. They live out a life of 40 to 50 years on average, growing the whole time, so an elder xoglio will be significantly larger than a teenager. Views on Other Races As the xoglio have an innate esteem of their elders they have a deep respect for the elves and dwarves, who lead lives ten times longer than them. Often they will interact with the aelfor of the woods they live in, and they have learned not to step on any toes and tread carefully in the presence of an elf of the woods. The only race they dislike are the warlike Uruks and their Urkob and Ogre cousins, who compete with the Xoglio for the niche of strongmen in the countryside. text.470: Character Creation Nobody knows for sure where the Skeox come from, and their short lifespans do not leave much room for ancestral knowledge. Their only redeeming trait is how fast they breed, allowing them to survive and fester in the plague ridden southeast of the empire. text.484: Character Creation multiracial; we all know what is being talked about here, although some would like it kept away from the public eye. It is important to remember that the civilized races around the middle sea are just that - races, and not separate species, and though through some quirk of  fate, godly intervention or magic they are wildly different from one another there is one thing that definitively proves that fact: They can breed. How this happens, and under what circumstances I will leave to more capable scholars and cheap romance novelists, but the fact remains. It doesn’t happen often, and their lives are often more difficult for straddling the cultures of their parents, but their stories deserve to be told all the same. Size Despite any crazy stories you may hear in a bar or tavern, the Parents of a halfling have to be within 1 size of one another, so an Ogre cannot procreate with a Urkob or ratling. Halfling characters are size 1 or normal size unless both of their parents are small or large sized. Language: Halfling characters have the following statistics changes at character creation: · +1 Empathy In addition, they have the following racial changes to their statistics based on their lineage: · Gain +1 to a statistic if both parents had +1 or greater to that statistic or if one parent has a +2 and the other doesn’t have a negative · Gain +2 to a statistic if both parents had +2 or greater to that statistic · Gain -1 to a statistic if both parents had a negative to that statistic or if one parent has a -2 or greater and the other doesn’t have a positive · Gain -2 to a statistic if both parents have a -2 or lower in that statistic In addition they Lose 1 Fate Point or their character is Infertile Skills: A multiracial character can choose skills from either of their parents lists. Half Human characters get 1 extra skill point to spend and can choose 2 skills not on the early upbringing racial skill list of the other parent. text.491: Character Creation As rare as they are, each halfling’s story is unique and listing every possible combination would be an exercise in frustration and excess. I have compiled a few more common ones here though for your perusement: Half elves The most common and least stigmatized mixed race is the half elf. A child of a low and high elf is still considered an elf by everyone except the more insular elven communities, and a child of humans and elves is still considered of high and righteous birth, especially if the parents were of higher social class. The majority of these half human marriages are political or at least monetary in nature - not that it’s impossible for an elf to love a human, but the intense emotional attachment that comes with caring for a child is something elves usually like to keep for someone who is able to live with them through centuries of life, not decades. Half orcs More rare than half elves, but probably the second most populous halfling is the half uruk. Despite imperial propaganda, it would be a misconception to say that half orcs solely come from a place of sexual violence. It’s true that when a marauding horde ravages through a land, a year or so later the number of half aurks increases dramatically, but rape is not a trait exclusive to Uruk armies, and outside of it there are many reasons people fall in love with Orcs, from political marriages, to convinence or even aesthetics - I’ve been told by many that the unique musculature of the orc physique is quite attractive from that point of view. The long and short of it is that there is a large population of orcs, and there are large populations of humans and other races interacting with them, and so statistically there will be many half-orcs. In the tribes of the deserts and savannah there is little distinction between Kaskine, Vaurl, Skeox and even Xoglio. Sometimes the tribes war with each other, and at other times they trade, and in many cases they intermarry and exchange families. It’s hard to say if the children of such pairings are lucky because the kind of predjudice they would face in the empire is the same that their parents would face; not more but definitely not less. Culturally these beastfolk usually take after one or another parent, generally the one in who’s tribe
text.499: Character Creation Add a Motive, Dream, Conflict and Bonds. This is really the core of the ‘Character’ of your character. These things define your character. In every scene they should be the aids to you to remind you what to do. It’s not necessary to write a long backstory for every player and every character, but it is helpful to think about these things when roleplaying out a character: Motive is your character’s general demeanor, and influences every action they take. This is not a concrete goal or objective, and not something achievable, but an abstract concept, purpose to strive towards. What keeps your character moving forward? Think of a method actor asking their director “What’s my motivation in this scene?” Whenever this question pops into your head, you should be able to look at your character sheet and remind yourself what your motivation is. Example Motivation: Hit on everything that movesObtain RichesGet a glorious death in combatHelp the helplessProve yourself to everyone in the room Dream is what you eventually want to acquire that would be enough for you. Unlike your motivation, a dream is a finite and achievable goal that your character has put in front of themselves. What does your character want to achieve? Giving your character a goal allows them to be proactive, making their own path in the world instead of just reacting to things happening around them. For the Game Master this is an indication of the part of the world you want to focus in on, and the plot threads you are most interested in exploring. Example Dreams: Run a tavern or shop that I ownKill the warlord enslaving my peopleTake revenge for my parentsFind the dragon and awaken himVanquish the blight Conflict is what prevents your character from achieving their dream. This can be an internal battle between your values, an evil empire, a system of injustice or anything else that would cause your character to get into problems. Don’t be afraid to get specific with this, the more you make up the easier it is for the Game Master to include it in their plans for your character. Conflict is what brings Drama to a game. While a dream is something you are moving towards, your conflict is something chasing after you, pushing at your heels.
text.503: Character Creation How does the character act differently from you, the player? By thinking through how this character acts and speaks differently from you, the player, it will be easier to embody this character as a separate personality from yourself. Example Mannerisms: Bombastic movementsFumbling prayer beadsA far eastern foreigner accentBreaking eye contactInvading the other person’s personal space Bonds are who your character is tied to in the setting you as players have decided to explore. What organizations they belong to, who their family is. Nobody exists in a vacuum, and the experiences they’re had in the past color their interactions going forward. Y our relationships tie you into the world in a literal sense. Y ou might want to take a look at the company’s affiliation and enemies. Who cares about your character? These can be allies, friends, family or even antagonists or someone you’ve run into before. If you’ d like, you can name another player’s character with their consent. Otherwise, this informs the Game Master what characters you want brought into the forefront of the game, or it can inform your dream or conflict. Example Bonds: My sister in the elven town of Imsoudiel is sick and needs medicineI have a wife back home waiting for meBork has saved my life a few timesI have a long lost father who left many years ago to fight the emperor but never returnedI am part of the imperial cataphracts as a paladin. Intrigue. No book could be completely understood from it’s cover. Not every character will have a backstory full of intrigue, mystery and secret they keep, but it can be good to think about what could someone find out if they prodded a little deeper into the character, and what clues could lead them there? Depending on your character, by now you might already know what their secrets and mysteries are, and while as a character it might be in your interest to keep such secrets safe, as a player you want others to be involved - after all why make up a story if nobody will ever find it out? The intrigue, if there is one, can also lead the Game master on to create plots relevant to the char -
text.506: Character Creation Barbarian - Ancestral customs : For every 8 points spent in the profession, Barbarians get an ancestral custom. The ancestral custom will have a tenet that the barbarian is forced to follow, and a trigger that activates it. When an ancestral custom is infringed on or otherwise triggered, you may exchange mind points for advantage points at a one to one ratio, up to a maximum of three points per custom. Abhors Magic: When you witness a magic item or magic. Cannot use magic items or spells My body is a temple: When your body is injured or someone intends to do it harm. Cannot wear armor or clothes that heavily obscures the body Freedom from chains: Whenever your freedom is infringed on, or you help others obtain freedom. Must not respect others socially higher than them and must stand up for others’ freedom. Vagabond: When you make your own goods and provisions instead of relying on money. Y ou must not gain a wealth status above vagabond Beastmaster: When you interact with an animal. Must not harm animals unless directly attacked. Battlemaster: When you enter battle with a raging scream. Y ou must never use underhanded tactics, nor attack from a sneaking position. · Write in: with the GM’s permission, specify a tenet and a trigger for your ancestral custom. Assuming a normal progression, Barbarians gain a new ancestral custom at 13 XP , 21 XP , 29 XP and 37 XP etc. Otherwise it might be useful to write down how many points you have spent since your last ancestral custom. Battle Rage: Barbarians when triggered can choose to enter a rage. Enraged, they ignore all conditions, wounds and damage, only stopping when they reach negative maximum Body points or choose to exit the Rage. The Game master takes note of any damage they take, and tells them once the rage is over. The Rage ends automatically when the Scene ends, and can have the character immediately fall unconscious, lose control of their limbs and in general suffer the effects of all the things they’ve ignored so far. In addition the Barbarian will take 1 point of exhaustion when their rage ends (-1 to Dodge, Consider, Perception and -1 to all rolls until the character rests)  While in a rage, a barbarian can treat adjacent numbers as causing a critical wound when attacking physically - for example rolling a 4 and 5 will be considered the same as rolling two matching 4s.

text.508: Character Creation Ranger - Well Traveled : For every 7 points spent in the profession Rangers gain a knowledge Domain. that can be changed in a week of studying something new. Y ou can ask the GM any questions about your domain and they must answer you truthfully to the best of their ability. The more specific your domain is, the more in depth your questions can be, for example knowledge of forests might not tell you where the elf hideout is, but knowledge of the Elvenglade woods where the elves are hiding in would. When in doubt, the GM should err on the side of telling you too much rather than too little.  When a new domain is gained, you can immediately choose one as long as it is plausible your character has been studying or living in it for the past week. Assuming a normal progression, Rangers gain one knowledge domain at 12 XP , 20 XP , 27 XP , 35 XP , etc. Otherwise it might be useful to write down how many points of ranger XP you have spent since your last domain. Ranger - Jack of All Trades: once a Ranger has spent 10 XP points in the profession, they may choose one feature of another profession and write it down as if it was theirs. If the feature requires a specialty that the ranger does not have access to, such as Cast Spell or Craft Rune, they may pay double XP for the specialty. A Ranger may not choose more than one Jack of All Trades feature, and may not change their Jack of All Trades feature once they take it. If a profession has more than one feature, the ranger is only able to emulate one. For example, a ranger may be able to emulate a wizard’s “Spell Researcher” Feature, but not their “Thaumaturgy” or “Ritual Caster” feature. When using this feature, the Ranger counts as having just spent 5 XP in the profession, the same amount as a starting character.If a feature gives special abilities or points for every point of XP spent in the profession, such as a Thief ’s Heist Feature awarding extra Heist points, the ranger counts as having half the XP of someone taking that profession. For example, when taking the Heist feature, the ranger immediately gets 1 Heist point, and will gain the next one at 20 XP instead of immediately gaining 2 Heist points(Every 10 XP insead of every 5 for the Thief), and if taking the Wizard’s Spell Researcher feature, the ranger gains 1 spell immediately and gets another spell at 16XP , then 24 XP etc (every 8 XP instead of every 4 for the Wizard).

Heist points allow you to declare a flashback at any time that lasts for one improve situation action but does not count as part of the usual turn order. This can be used during combat for a feint or sneak attack set up or can be used during story beats for anything the rogue desires. The difficulty of the roll is set by the GM based on the plausibility of the event happening.Heist points can be spent as advantage points while describing a flashback to increase the odds of its success. Normal advantage points cannot be spent to improve flashback rolls. Assuming a normal progression, Thieves start with 1 heist point and gain one more at 15 XP , 20 XP , 25 XP , etc. Otherwise it might be useful to write down how many points of thief XP you have spent since your last heist point. Backstab - Thieves are cunning fighters who have little in the way of honor when fighting. When a Thief attacks a target by surprise, whether by Deception or Stealth or describing some other underhanded tactic they use while fighting they can increase their chance of a Critical Hit and they can make the wound hurt more. Unlike other characters, they can expend Advantage points to nudge their die roll down as Many times as they have Maximum Heist points + 1, instead of just the usual 1. The number of current Heist Points doesn’t matter, only the total maximum. This can be used to roll a critical strike on an opponent by making the two dice rolls equal. If they cause a wound on such an attack, they can any remaining Advantage points on the Damage die roll to nudge the die roll upwards, something not usually possible at all. One advantage can be used to increase the damage die by 1 point, same as for lowering. For Example, a Rogue with 1 Heist point who is attacking an unaware target and rolls a 6 and 4 can expend 1 Advantage point to nudge the 6 to a 4 and roll a Critical result and inflict a wound. Assuming the attack hits the target, they can then use advantage points to change their die result upwards by 1 instead of adding to the total damage, so if they rolled a 4 (Ripped Muscle) result, they could expend 2 Advantage points to get a 6 (Gushing Blood) result instead.

Ritual caster - when a warlock casts a spell, they can reduce their spell’s cost by 1 for every 5 minutes of active preparation they spend, drawing circles, pentagrams, setting up candles, chanting to their dark lord, etc. up to 3 points of cost reduced to a minimum of 0 cost. text.517: Character Creation Priest - Divine spellcaster: Choose a patron saint with 2 tenets. They have two schools of magic + Holy magic. The tenets should be passive like “cannot drink alcohol” or “cannot spill blood on temple grounds” Can also include actions you take that nobody would oppose you in that are easy to succeed Every 5 points of XP spent in the profession, a priest gains a covenant. The covenant must be active like “must help the innocent” or “must spread their worship” . Has to be something difficult to accomplish for your character, but a goal that can be worked towards. While resting, they can pray for a number of miracles equal to the number of active covenants they are in the process of fulfilling, which are essentially a spell from either of the three lores of magic of the patron God. A Priest can alter the spells they have every time they pray, and the player can make up spells they wish to use later at any time, as long as they mark the spells they have active. If they fail any of their tenets they cannot use their spells until they appeal for penance during prayer. The GM must warn the player that a course of action will subvert one of their tenets. To cast a miracle, Priests must use an action and roll a Mysticism - Create Miracle specialty roll above the spell difficulty and winds of chaos. They also expend an amount of mind points equal to the spell cost. A Priest gains back half their Arcane points on a long rest (overnight) or a break (1 hour) during which they do not change their spells. If the character completes their covenant, such as overthrowing a tyrant who was suppressing their religion they can replace their covenant with a new one and add a tenet. As long as they do not break that tenet they gain 1 extra active spell they can cast. Every 5 points spent in the profession, Priests gain a new covenant, which increases the number of covenants they might be following and therefore their active spells. Assuming a normal progression, Priests start with 1 covenant and gain a new covenant at 15 XP , 20 XP , 25 XP , 30 XP  etc. Otherwise it might be useful to write down how many points of Priest XP you have spent since your last covenant.

text.531: Character Creation Diplomat - Contacts: Every 7 points spent in the profession Diplomats gain a new contact. This must be set up in roleplay either with an in person meeting or an exchange of letters. By spending a week chatting up a character, they can be made a new diplomatic contact. The number of active contacts can never exceed the maximum amount a diplomat can have, which is 1 for every 7 points spent in the profession. A character outwardly hostile to the diplomat character cannot be made into a contact, and the diplomat would find this out immediately upon trying. Contacts cannot be more than two steps socially removed from the diplomat. Diplomatic contacts will not betray the character, will not lie to the character and will answer any question the character has to the best of their ability. Diplomatic characters are willing to expend an amount of resources equal to the daily expenditure of someone two social strata lower than them for the diplomat at any time, or equal to their own level expenditure once, at which point they stop being diplomatic contacts and must be courted again. Social Strata Willing to spend at will Willing to spend once Vagabond -- 3 Denars (a drink, a club) Peasant 2 Assess (a note, a candle) 40 Denars (a potion, a knife) Middle Class 3 Denars (a drink, a tool) 5 Aureus Rich 40 Denars (a potion, a knife) 3 Solidus Emperor 5 Aureus 10 Solidus If a player does something obviously against their contacts’ interest, they are forewarned by the GM that this action will cost them a contact (The character would know). If the player proceeds with the action the contact is removed from the active contacts list. Assuming a normal progression, Diplomats gain one more maximum contact at 12 XP , 20 XP , 27 XP , 35 XP , etc. Otherwise it might be useful to write down how many points of diplomat XP you have spent since your last contact. When a new contact is gained, you can immediately choose one as long as it is plausible your character has been interacting with them for the past week and they are not actively hostile to you. Diplomats can expend a string to cut down their contact acquiring time to 1 day, or 2 strings to make it instant, as long as they stay under their total number of contacts.
text.536: Character Creation After you’ve decided on your character’s early life and profession, you should have a character with 10 to 12 Experience Points (XP) spent.  Depending on the story you all want to tell, this could be your character or you could spend some more XP on them, exactly as you had before. During play, you might earn more Experience Points by accomplishing goals of your character or role playing through their motivation and conflicts. It won’t happen every session, but whenever you succeed in something your characters set out to do, you should probably get a point. If your GM gives you an XP , mark it down on your sheet. Spending XP Whenever you rest for half a day or more, you can spend up to 1 Point from those you earned on your character. Whenever you take a long weekend, you can spend up to 5 points from those you accumulated. This represents your character processing the events, learning lessons and making plans for their next move. When you spend a point of XP on your character, you can spend it to improve your Statistics Bonus, your proficient skills or your proficient specialties. Y our proficient skills are any of those you already have points spent in AND any of those your profession offers you. Y our proficient specialties are any of those your Profession lists. Y ou do not need to have improved your statistic bonus to improve a skill, not have improved a skill to improve a specialty. For example, you can spend a point to improve your Longswords roll without spending any points in Smash or Accuracy. Whatever you spend it on, the first time you improve it, it will cost 1XP the first time you improve it, 2XP the second time, and 3 XP the third time. This means that on a one day rest, you can only improve things you have not previously improved before. If the GM allows you, you can spend XP on specialties and skills outside of those you are proficient in. The GM can also specify if they will cost double the normal amount or not. text.553: Equipment Weight A character can lift a certain amount of weight comfortably. Items have a weight, and a character carrying too much will slow down until they can no longer pick up that weight. For simplicity an item will have either a trivial, light, average or heavy weight. Trivial items are things like coins, papers, small gems, etc. 100 Trivial items will add up to 1 kg of carried weight Light items are things like arrows, other projectiles, small stones. 10 Light items add up to 1kg Average items are your basic weapons and small items. They are assumed to be 1kg. If a weight isn’t listed or talked about you can assume it is of average weight Heavy items are anything past 1 kg and are listed in terms of their bulk and weight, roughly equal to the square root of their weight in kg but being more or less depending on the unwieldiness of the item. Comfortable - A character is comfortable up to their 10 + Athletics - Lifting rating. They suffer no issues while walking around with this much weight. This is called the carry weight. This value is multiplied by size Encumbered - A character is encumbered when they are above their carry weight but less than the Comfortable + 10 + Resources - Encumbrance rating. They can act as normal but cannot sprint. This value is multiplied by size. A character who is encumbered has a disadvantage on their Endurance check should they choose to do a forced march. Over encumbrance - a character who is over their encumbrance weight cannot sprint and does not gain their run bonus if they move twice in one turn. In addition for every full 10 kg they are above their encumbrance limit they reduce their move speed by 1m Large Items - the encumbrance represents your ability to carry many different items for long stretches of time, and not your character’s maximum lifting potential when adrenaline is pumping and life is on the line. That sort of situation is better handled by a Athletics - Lifting improve situation test with a difficulty set by the GM. If you want a number that your character can deadlift, take your encumbrance in kg and multiply by 10.
text.554: Equipment wear establishes your connections, status, clout and how you operate.Clothing is a light item, and doesn’t add weight to a character when it’s worn. A character starts with clothes of their appropriate social strata, which they do not need to pay for, although it is also not particularly fashionable. A naked character is much more sensitive to environmental changes than a clothed one, taking a point of exhaustion every day and counting as one category higher on the Extreme Temperature table if it’s applicable. Fashion Clothes are the easiest and fastest way of differentiating yourselves from the masses. The cost of a piece of clothing is dependent on the materials and the labor of the artisans needed.  Wearing the clothes of the social strata you are in isn’t a necessity - people can tell if you have money and power by other means, but if you’re trying to make a statement about yourself, the fastest and easiest way to go about it is wearing appropriate clothes. Social Strata Examples Material Cost Fashionable Cost Vagabond Old and Tattered clothing 5 Denar 25 Denars Peasant Linens and Cottons, wraps and 12 Denar 100 Denars Middle Class Leathers and quality trimmed pants125 Denar 600 Denars Rich Silks, Colored dyes, Quality arti- sans450 Denar 2300 Denars Emperor Intricate patterns woven by multi- ple artisans2000 Denar 10000 Denars Function Other than a fashion statement, clothing protects us from the elements. Certain clothes are better at that then others, although these clothes use different materials and are harder for dealing with. For example instead of 10 Denar of Cotton or Linen, they could be made of heavy leathers and multi materials worth 75 denar. The materials are harder to work with at all and doubly so to make pretty while retaining their resilience. For this reason, Temperature Resistant clothing costs 5 times the normal amount. In exchange these clothes will halve Exhaustion from adverse temperatures (rounding down, so 1 Exhaustion becomes 0), and will halve damage from Burning or Freezing.

text.580: Magic Magic Making a Spell: Wizards, Rune smiths, Diplomats, Alchemists, Warlocks and Priests get to make up spells they can use during the game. To do so, they need a Magical Domain mode and powers . Those characters that can create a spell should do so when making/modifying their character, not in the middle of a game. If they can swap out between different spells when resting, such as Warlocks and Priests, they can create a few extra spells and indicate which are prepared after they rest. magical domain describes what is the engine that allows this spell to function. Depending on your character, you might be able to select from multiple magical domains but each spell can only have one magical domain . Magical domains determine which powers you can select from. A spell can have up to 7 powers and modifiers as the player desires. Each power has a certain Spell point cost and domain prerequisite. Y ou can only add a power to your spell if the domain prerequisite is ANY or contains your specified domain. Multiple levels of the same spell power can be taken without counting as separate powers. For example a spell can do +4 Damage if it takes Damage 4 times for +8 Spell points. This still counts as only 1 power for the purpose of the 7 modifiers or powers limit. Some powers and modifiers have options you can take together with the power or modifier. Although these modify the cost they do not count as a separate power towards the powers limit. The combined Spell points determine the cast difficulty of a spell (The number you need to roll to cast the spell successfully). When calculating this, always add every Spell point that can be added or subtracted, then multiply the total number by any factors that multiply or divide the total number. (sum of all additive modifiers) x (sum of all multipliers) Each spell also has a mental cost which determines how strenuous it is for the wizard or sorcerer to cast a particular spell. The cost is determined by taking the final difficulty, rounding it up to the next tens digit, taking that tens digit and adding 1 to it. The average spell will cost between 1 and 3 points when cast.
text.581: Magic Casting a spell: Spells are cast in different ways. Sorcerers Wizards, Warlocks and Priests create their spells in advance and cast them when necessary. To cast them, the character rolls a check in a relevant skill and specialty and must pass the cast difficulty. If they pass, the spell effect happens, and if they fail, the spell backfires, hurting them. Either way, they lose as many Mind points as the spell costs. Elves, Diplomats, Alchemists and Rune smiths create their spells beforehand. Because every spell is Stable their spells are limited by the relevant craft spell specialty and cannot be pushed further. Their spells also cannot take advantage of ritual casting. Generally their spells will be weaker than those of true casters due to this. In exchange, they never have to spend Mind points when casting spells, and their spells never fail. Spell Default assumptions Certain spell powers will rely on modifiers to define what and how they target. If those modifiers are not taken, these are the default assumptions of a spell: Range: The caster must touch their target, being within less than 1 meter of them.Duration: The spell lasts for 1 combat round, or 12 seconds. If the Lasting power isn’t taken, all spells last until the beginning of the caster’s next turn. The spell has a Vocal component which the caster must say, and is accompanied by light and sound, casting a spell is obvious to the onlooker and might even be noticeable from some distance away. If desired, the player can write down an incantation they can recite while casting their spell! Targets: One Size 1 or above creature, or as many creatures below size 1 as to make up to 1. For example, a caster can cast a spell on five size 1/5 creatures as long as they can touch them. Powers and modifiers - unless otherwise stated in the profession, a spell can only have up to 7 different powers and modifiers. Options under a modifier do not count to this limit - for example a spell with the Damage Power can take Armor Piercing as part of that same power. Modifiers and Powers with 0 cost do not count towards the 7 power and modifier limit.
text.588: Magic Basic magic type, sparkles and unicorns. Deals force damage if any. Most common magic type and the default if one is not specified. Can be cast anytime. Fire Domain Automatically applies Light 2 and Damage 2 , which do not count towards the cost of the spell. Needs a source of fire for the spell to cast (unless the spell creates fire). The spell cannot be a stealth spell. Water Domain Area of effect is Doubled automatically for the spell. Needs a source of water for the spell to cast (unless the spell creates water). If the spell includes the power Apply Force at tier 10 or above, the spell can manipulate up to 1000 liters of water. If this is combine Earth Domain Automatically add Apply Force 2 to the spell, which must be dealt with somehow. Needs a source of earth for the spell to cast (unless the spell creates earth). If the spell includes the power Apply Force at tier 15 or above, the spell can manipulate up to cubic meter of soil or dirt per its area of effect. Air Domain Needs a source of air for the spell to cast (unless the spell creates air), and  If the spell includes the power Apply Force, the spell can manipulate a cube meter of Air per its area of effect which can then be caught with sails, parachutes etc. Necromancy Domain Dark energies from beyond the veil, where even gods fear to tread. This type of magic is extremely illegal in the empire and any civilized place. Holy Domain Magic sourced by one of the gods. Need to have the gods favor to cast the spell. Mind Domain Magic that controls the mind. Must have a mind to manipulate for the spell to cast - does not work on monsters and people and creatures with 0 empathy. While more accepted than Necromancy magic, some applications of this magic are considered extremely illegal Illusion Domain Magic that controls what people see and perceive. A trained eye will be able to catch the subtle differences between reality and the illusion. When Taking Illusion Powers in a spell as well as the “Help Statistic/Skill/Specialty” Power, Ignore the spell points of the Illusion Powers up to the amount spent on the “Help Statistic/Skill/Specialty” Power
text.591: Magic Powers Mode (only one): Spell Default standard check. Roll 2d10 choose lowest and spend advantage as normal. Unpredictable +3 SP Double the value of the dice rolled when the spell is cast. When the lowest die is a 5, add 10 instead, when the lowest die is 8 add 16, etc. Stable +0 SP When casting, do not roll. Cannot cause a magical mishap, nor use advantage to modify the roll; either you have enough casting specialty to cast it or you do not. A Stable spell cannot have any other modifiers that modify the roll. Modifiers Imbue +0SP Can only be used to enchant an item. For the duration of the spell, the item acts as if it casts this spell. If the spell has any properties, such as damage, they are added to any properties of the item. Imbued Spells with the touch range must have someone willingly touch the object or else have someone use it versus the target’s dodge rating, and imbued Spells with the attack power must include a skill check from an operator towards the target’s Dodge. A spell used on an imbued weapon can add damage or alter traits of a weapon, but if the spell adds area of effect  or otherwise has multiple targets, only the target hit by the weapon takes the damage of the weapon, all the other ones are only affected by the spell.
