text.998: Living in the World What do you do with the limited time you have Y ou’re gonna die. It’s an inevitable fact of life and the stories we want to tell with Mortal Reins. Characters in Mortal Reins won’t gain immortality or save the world (although they might try) - the journey and where they end up is what’s important. Perhaps just changing their own life or that of a small community might be enough for them, or maybe they will be a flame that burns bright and quickly. Corruption and Collapse The world is in the middle of a crisis - perhaps the worst it’s seen since its history (although if you listen to some of the older races, perhaps not). The great empires, peacekeepers of the last age, have collapsed and a man is no longer free to till their own soil nor is work a sure way to prosperity. The systems that used to work to preserve these empires now works against them, as the monetary institutions are used to fatten the rich and steal from everyone. Bribes are accepted and encouraged on every level, the law is what those in power say and obligations are just lip service. Those in power have gotten so used to milking the teat that they either fail to realize that the world around them is collapsing or actively encourage it to further their own shortsighted interests. The Churn The world is constantly changing - if you look away for but a second the entire landscape might change, both politically, economically and often physically. The wise ask for payment up front, because when tasked to travel for some time they might find that the people hired them are no longer in power when they get back. Likewise, only a fool pays before a job is complete, because the workers will surely run off with it. On Forces beyond control Nobody can be everywhere at once except adversity. Everywhere heroes aren’t, the world withers a little bit. But even when confronted, the forces involved might be so great that the best bet a person might have is to simply move aside, lest they be crushed underfoot.
text.1005: Living in the World Nuterra The rest of the chapter is dedicated to a potential world for your characters to explore, a vague fantastical analogue to Europe in the late 300s to 600s AD. It is an intentionally zoomed out view of the world, with key details omitted; these blank spaces are there for players to fill in with their own stories and ideas. The use of this world is entirely optional, and the ruleset can be used in any fantastical setting from books, movies or other media you wish for, or a world created by one or many of the players of the game. The purpose of this chapter is to spur imagination and create a potential common area from which to build your section of the world, fitting into a greater tapestry that all players can be aware of. History of the World of Nuterra Time Before Time - a great deal of time more than 5000 years before the empire The origins of the world are murky and full of conflicting tales. I will attempt to relate to you, reader, what I have learned poring over the oldest elvish texts, but the secret keepers in their libraries worked their job well. Do not expect any sort of accuracy in this section, read it more as a collection of myths than a solid history. It is said that In the beginning, there was nothing but dust, material and magical, scattered in an even soup throughout the universe. The magic had been there for a long time before it coalesced into anything more than a nebulous form of power, existing as both spirit, energy and matter at the same time. Over time, these particles grew closer together and formed the three primordial beings. Beyond time and space were they: The Great Star Bird that soared the skies, scattering stars in it’s path. The Great World Turtle, who’s shell crumbled off and formed the continents and spawned oceans and the Fungus, that occupied itself with everything in between the sky and the ground. They all lived their lives in harmony and peace for an indeterminate amount of time between a second and infinity until one day, when the Great Star Bird flew too close to the Great World Turtle and was struck by a piece of debris from the turtle’s shell. This caused its wings to burn away and left behind only a single feather, which landed on the mushrooms growing on the turtle’s back and sprouted our world.
text.1012: Living in the World The first era of mortals was called the First Age, or the Age of Myth and Bronze. This was a time of wonder and exploration, where people used stone tools and hunted animals with spears and bows. As the years passed, they learned how to use metal, and created weapons and armor. Civilizations rose around fertile river valleys and near coasts. Cities were built and then abandoned, forgotten by time. The art of writing was invented and some of the earliest books were written.As the centuries wore on, the cities became bigger and more complex. Back then, it was no big deal still for a mortal to wield magic without any study, and the priest-kings of the valley of Kelmp ruled with an iron fist. However, as the knowledge of magic spread and became more refined, the kings were overthrown and replaced with wizards, who became powerful and wealthy. This shift caused the first collapse, as sorcerers and wizards struggled to understand the magics they were wielding without the help of the gods. Many of the civilizations fell to a mysterious sea-peoples; the Xoglio, perhaps? records from this time are as unclear as they are rare. Although perhaps I judge the scribes of the time too harshly. Many cities fell apart without the necessary goods to feed their people, and more fell to chaos and revolt. Such troubles plagued the land that the current crisis plaguing the empire seems more of a small hiccup. After the troubles were over, the Aelimfor were the first to recover. Age of Magic and Elves - 1500 to 1000 years before the empire The Age of Magic and Elves began with the rise of a new race, the Aelim. They were the descendants of the gods who fled to the surface after the war in heaven, and took the form of men. When the younger mortal races lost access to their writings and histories, they fell into chaos, but this was not so for the long lived elves, who remembered the old cities and civilizations fondly, and sought to restore the world as it once was. The great conqueror of the Aelim, who would later be known as Elenar was at once a warrior, a prophet and a king who led his people to greatness and prosperity. He united the lands under one banner, and built the city of Eleder. So powerful was his will that the kingdom or Haliahra and Tymeria are still ruled by elves to this day, although their subjects often are not. Still, his dream of a world united by Aelim rule was not to last past his death. His sons and generals all took pieces of his empire for their own, and insulated themselves from their subjects and courts, surrounding themselves with their elven comrades. It was in this way that they made rebellion all but inevitable.
text.1015: Living in the World The Scorb is a city-state located on the shores of the middle sea, on a peninsula jutting out to the sea, and was home to the largest population of humans. The city-state’s main exports were salt and iron, but they also produced fine weapons and armor, which they traded to other nations for food and other goods. Their chief export was salt, which was brought down from the northern mountains and shipped south along the coast. The weakness of the other kingdoms and oligarchies after the Scouring made Scorb a powerful entity, but it was its war with Tymeria that put it on the map. In a daring raid, the Scorbians captured the fortress of Tymeria, killing most of the defenders and taking their princess hostage. They demanded the release of the hostages held by Tymeria, but the King of Tymeria refused. After a vote, the consuls of Scorb executed the Tymerian princess and all the elves they had captured, then burned the city to the ground.Scorb was a powerful nation for many years, expanding its borders and building ships to bring in trade goods from far off places. However, after many decades of expansion, the country began to suffer from internal unrest and economic decline. That was when Marcus Tabius took charge of the nation and established the Scorbosi Empire. Pax Imperial The Pax Imperial was established shortly after the fall of the Scorbian republic, and marked a new golden age for mankind. It was ruled by the emperor, who had absolute power over the entire empire. Other races and nations were integrated into the empire, and it’s borders expanded to the east and west. With the aid of magic and technology, the empire became the greatest power in the world, and the capital city of Tarsys was constructed as the seat of power for the empire on the eastern shore of the middle sea. The high elves retreated to their fortresses in the Echoes Isles, and the only competitor to Scorbus was the kingdom of Haliahra. The Current Crisis - 584 years since the empire was founded
text.1017: Living in the World Cosmology of a Mortal World Other planes - do they exist? Maybe for gods and other endless entities like them, but Mortals like me and you are left to wonder. From what the magi and other practitioners of magic are able to deduce, an invisible aether surrounds our world, normally imperceptible to us. Various particles and energies are able to move through this layer, completely non-interactive with the physical realm except through the application of mag-ic. It is in this layer all around us that gods exercise their force, and the conscious and unconscious manipula-tion of this layer allows us mortals to make use of magic. Although we do not often see the manipulations of the aether, we can infer certain things about it. For example, while a person lives, their soul is bound to their body, and they have a certain field around them, pushing and adjusting the particles of arcana. If the physical body is killed or in much more rare cases the soul is destroyed, the other component can only remain for a few months. Much as we see a dead body rot, wither and become earth, a soul without a host will fade away, lost in the churn of the invisible aether. Much like decomposition, this process can take a variable amount of time based on many factors, but often the soul lasts as a ghost for a period of a few months. This is how ghosts are able to haunt the places they died at, how necromancers and priests can communicate with and bring back the dead. With this knowledge we can infer what the gods are. These entities are able to tell us anything we want to hear and are incentivized to do so - but from what small part we can verify we know this: Consciousness can exist in the magic around us. Beings can live entirely on their own in the aether, and affect it without having a physical body. Usually they choose to coalesce in places with less people due to the effect a soul has on the magical fields around them, either in the sky or deep below the earth (physical barriers of course being at best trivial formalities and at worst completely imperceptible to these beings) but occasionally they will live with the people, at the tops of mountains or in lakes, places where they can keep themselves whole.
text.1024: Living in the World symbiote are larger than what they would have gained on their own. This is where the imperial angels and apostles come from. The lead entity in this system is unable to process the prayers of so many worshippers and hands out regions and individual believers to others in a perverse mirror of the feudal systems of the mortals. Even then, each of the minor gods strives for a larger piece. The Antiholian Heresy for example was a movement in the breakaway city of Ysier lead by former priests and philosophers that stated that the god emperor of Scorbus was in no way divine, and the gods in the creed were simply keeping up a ruse to maintain their hold on the people in the largest religion in the world. If they are to be believed, what a coup it was for a relatively minor god to come in and take over the position of divine emissary to all the citizens of the city state, the oligarchs of which could no longer abide by the worship of the emperor. Mantling and Sharpening We’ve already discussed the ways in which a mortal ruler or anyone with sufficient believers to offer can become a god-symbiote, gaining some of the powers of a god, but true mantling is much, much more rare. A mortal becoming a god can only come from a powerful gathering of magic currents and worshipers. I myself have only known of one dark wizard to have become divine. His true name I shall not utter here, but when he was a mortal they called him Halim Al Musa. Driven to madness by his own frailness and mortality, he attempted to ascend to the position of a god. From my understanding he did not like what was in store once he peered into that darkness. What use is immortality without the mortal flesh to enjoy it? What's slightly better understood is the idea of Sharpening - when a god that was previously totally or partially in the aether attains a physical form. This happens once every elven generation or so, and always comes with a calamitous event, volcanoes erupting, tidal waves and the such. Many gods spend millennia plotting such an event with their cultists, involving bloodlines, sacrifices and proper stellar alignment, but the result is rarely as long lasting as it is spectacular - the nature of such an event unites the other gods and the mortal realm against the sharpened god, whether that be a dragon, leviathan or some other monstrous form, and within a few decades the god is destroyed, having poured much of itself into the physical form.
text.1026: Living in the World Scobrus Empire A human empire encompassing most of the known world, it was responsible for a long period of peace after its armies conquered the different people all around it. Now it has fallen into decay and is being ripped apart by rebellions and invasions. Origins Although it began hundreds of years ago from rather humble beginnings, the empire soon grew to dominate its neighbors and control much of the known world through the might of its legions and magical siege engineers. Although it has faced crises before and come back from them, it might have reached a breaking point. The rulers (of which there are now several, each claiming they are the legitimate lord of the empire) have withdrawn into their keeps behind thick walls, leaving the common people to fend for themselves. Soldiers and other functionaries of the state are no more than brigands wandering the roads and collecting protection money from those they can get their hands on. Religions Although known to persecute cults in the past, the empire is generally tolerant of various religions; as long as the religions submit to the cult of the emperor. The divinity of the emperor has recently been put into question, what with the many pretenders to the throne and quick succession and murder of the empire’s rulers. This allowed the various minor gods to gain new followers - and new power. Coups, Countercoups, civil wars Despite the cult of the emperor claiming their divinity, Recent events have proven that the emperors are very very mortal. In fact, killing the emperor has become a very lucrative business; as long as you can ride the wave to the top. The emperor’s guards assassinate them as often as guard them, and shadowy figures rule from behind the throne, thinking it safer than claiming it for themselves. Those in the countryside have stopped counting the new emperors, and regions have broken off from the empire entirely. Plague & Natural Disasters Internal problems would be one thing, but they’re not the only disaster pressuring the empire. A series of poor harvests have caused a food crisis among the poor. As if that wasn’t enough, a plague ravages the eastern, more heavily populated parts of the empire. Black buboes and putrid bubbles pop over the skin, and soon the patient expires. Whole towns are left empty in its wake. Even the Skeox, often called the heralds of the plague, fall victim to it in huge numbers and run to escape it more than to spread it.
text.1033: Living in the World The empire to the east of Scorobus is situated among a river valley and mountain plateau, the Haliahrans are a dynasty of elves who long ago conquered the region. Although over the following centuries they interbred with their subjects and diluted their elven blood, there was always a tension between those at the top and the primarily human inhabitants of the empire. Pressures from the even further east Recently, roving tribes and horseback raiders have become an increasingly large thorn in the side of the empire. The steppe peoples have always been there, at the periphery of the empire, but the kings of old had been able to pay them off or scary them away with a show of force. The final conflict with Scorbus has left the current emperor low both on cash and manpower, and now raiders stray further into his territory than ever before, even threatening major population centers. Scorbus Haliahran wars As long as the two empires have bordered each other, they have had wars. Often using proxies and small invasions, they prodded at each other, with a mighty struggle occurring every generation or two. The Scorobians had conquered the ancient homes of the elves which every Haliahran emperor coveted, and wanted more territory besides. 10 years ago, with the internal collapse and rebellion threatening Scorbus, Sun God Emperor General Jiyuk III marched further into Scorbus than any before her. She thought this would finally be the war to end all wars and destroy her ancient rival. Instead, the scorbians rallied together to face the external threat, and the Haliahran armies were smashed. It was her own empire that collapsed soon after, and Jiyuk took her own life, leaving a son behind to rule in her stead. Collapse Without the mighty armies and strong wizards to keep the population in line, the subservient majority had their opportunity to throw off their chains and cast down the rulers. Despite this, the collapse was not a violent revolution but rather a slow and gradual process. More and more offices had to be filled with humans and other people of the empire as the number of elves dwindled, and the new stewards were more interested in filling their pockets than running an empire. The army was disbanded and local leaders took charge. In places with a significant army presence the generals took control, setting up their own fiefdoms and kingdoms.
text.1036: Living in the World The Elder Races Aelfor The elves are the oldest race of the world, having their own great empires in antiquity and controlling the world before the other races came into their prime. Their civilizations collapsed at the end of the First age, and although they were able to carve large kingdoms afterwards, they were eventually overtaken by humans all over the world, and subsumed by the empire in all places except the east, where eventually they too became so interbred with the humans that the distinction between the two races stopped mattering. Echos Isles Holdouts of “pure” elves in the eastern half of the middle sea, this glittering kingdom keeps its independence with shrewd diplomacy and large amounts of magic. Their ships, though rare, are generally unmolested by empire nor pirate ships, as they are known for their ferocity in battle. High elves are extremely useful to have around, as their understanding of magic is second to none - and yet you should never trust an elf. They think themselves loftier than any of the other races and are often seen in the shadows near many of the empires darkest moments. Moon Forest Although the high elves of the isles like to call themselves the last of their race, this is not strictly speaking true. It is known by all children of the empire that elves exist throughout the great forest north. They come in the middle of the night to kidnap children and replace them with changelings who will in turn be raised by good citizens of the empire only to steal from them and run off once they grow older, or the parents grow suspicious. Travelers to the northern wood seldom come back, as the elves are strong  guardians of trees there. Xogliofor Undersea cities & the First Age collapse It is known that at the end of the first age a sea peoples came from the ocean to wipe out the elven empires that at the time prospered. The elves had grown decadent and interdependent, and once one kingdom was destroyed the rest were easy to fold. Although little records remain of that time, and the elves that lived then are tight lipped, it is theorized that the first age collapse was the fault of the Xogliofor, who came from undersea cities to pillage the elves at the behest of their sea deity. If true, that would be very worrisome for the empire: not only would this mean that there are significantly more Xoglio than originally predicted, it would mean that rather than rugged and individualistic they are
text.1038: Living in the World It is a time for great changes, and nowhere is this more clear than in the migrating people coming from all directions into the empire. From traders, to invaders to simple refugees looking for a new life - each has their own reasons to move into Scorbus. Changing climate The poor harvest happening inside the empire has not been an isolated incident. Whether through a freak accident or a trick of some god, harvests have been poor all over the world. The temperature has been growing colder and drier, and in many places people have been starving for much longer than in the empire. Motivated by stories and tales, they make for Scorbus in the vain hope that their pastures will be more plentiful. Newcomer attitude The outlook of the migrants is as varied as the number of them on the streets of Ancinia. But there are some commonalities that separate them from citizens in the empire. Generally speaking, they are more communal and collectivist than the people who grew up in the relative safety of the empire, and value loyalty to their clan over even their own life at times. This has led some confused citizenry to wrongly assume they are more friendly and honest than the fair people of Storbus. Nothing could be further from the truth - an immigrant is just as likely to lie, steal and murder as any of our good people - they’ll just do it for their clan rather than themselves. Far off pressures Some of the tribes ride not to greener pastures and the relative prosperity of the empire, but to escape an as of yet unforeseen threat. Whether its invaders or monsters, those who flee rarely want to recollect the experiences of their past. We must be ever vigilant in our study of these occurrences. Minor Religions and Cults Each individual tribe has their own beliefs and deities, but a few larger sects have emerged, especially to the south. As the different tribes meet in the melting pot of the empire, their ancestral beliefs merge and evolve, the various small gods fighting it out for power. None have yet grown as large as even the smallest of our empire’s gods, but this disparity makes them try harder, spending more of their power on pacts and boons for their followers in an effort to gain more worship.
text.1043: Living in the World Scorbian emperors of past have in their infinite wisdom and glory often went on military campaigns into those regions to keep their neighbors weak and in check. Distracted as they were by problems from inside the empire, they allowed the Rymon to rebuild. Some fools thought that this would work to the advantage of the empire, that the Rymons would unwittingly protect Scorbus while the succession crisis could be dealt with, but nothing could be further from the truth. When Zaurk Bubon showed up the cowards fled, bypassing the breakaway state of Sherion on their longboats and sailed into the soft underbelly of the south-west of the empire. The people there, long used to peace, were unable to drive back these invaders, and now their ships pester the entire western half of the middle sea. Netheren raiders The netheren come from the same steppes as the Valodar, and in the absence of their rival, these aurk necromancer tribes have grown in prominence, raiding deep into Haliahran and Scorbian territory. They come at night on great wolves and take citizens back to their lands. For what purpose even I do not know. Vogyar peoples The Vogyar was a xoglio tribe that used to live in the swamps to the northeast of the empire. Their lizardfolk warriors were a strong addition to the imperial forces when used as auxiliaries, but instead of seeing the service that was bestowed upon them by the emperor as the gift it was they turned against him, raiding the empire from east to west and even reaching the walls of the capital. Although eventually dispersed, they were not destroyed and their folk still live in those lands of the empire they marched through. Kaskines tribes - travellers The Kaskine has never been ones to settle down, preferring to move in and out of the empire; a constant headache for the bureaucrats and tax collectors. After the collapse of Haliahran though, they have been noticed inside Scorbus more and more frequently - perhaps escaping the chaos there, or perhaps just looking for more lucrative markets. It is known that many of them worship the relatively new god Sumer, and have been spotted prolethesizing his word across the many cities of the empire. Such heretical activity has been and should continue to be punished wherever it is found. Even more concerning, the Kaskines can’t even seem to agree what flavor of their god to follow, with some extolling the virtues of Sonnon and some of Renon. Amusing as their infighting is, it still destabilizes the empire and should be stopped.
text.1053: Living in the World Each character starts the game with knowledge of 1 language, usually Scorbosi, which is the commoner’s language, or aeldari, which is the lingua franca of the rich. Each character can pick up a passing understanding in another language for 1XP spent and an appropriate time studying it or living immersed in it. If a characters don’t share the same language the players can only interact by hand gestures. Scorbosi The most common language spoken throughout the empire, it is easy enough to understand for any newcomer. Likewise every region has their own slightly different take on the language, as it inevitable dips Sounds The language has no u vowel, and differentiates between long and short vowels, here represented by doubling up the vowels Grammar A sentence follows the Subject Verb Object word order. Adjectives follow nouns. Conjugations are used to represent past and present time state. There are separate articles when describing someone of a higher or lower rank than the speaker. Words Writing The language is written in an alphabet, usually by scribes. There is a high art of calligraphy involved in writing the language, however there is also a simplified version used for bookkeeping. text.1091: Living in the World The language uses every sound a humanoid mouth is capable of making, including 9 vowels, vowel harmonies and 34 consonants. Roots of words often mean abstract concept or emotions that change over millennia as the language spoken is imbued with new meaning by those who speak it. Rather than a collection of sounds meant to communicate a specific term they are more like sharing memories that are vaguely reminiscent of the point the speaker attempts to make. Writing Writing in the language takes the shape of hieroglyphic pictures that represent the root of the word in limdari. Over millennia, these pictures have become more and more stylized, but they still represent a concept rather than a sound. Limdari The high gift is a stricter form of aeldari where the words actually mean something - and the origin of their meanings in current aeldari. Speaking limdari is fraught with danger however, as the words themselves are a conduit for magic - so often they are subtly different from the root words in simple aeldari for safety reasons. Soudari Because of the nature of the language, the meaning behind the same phrase spoken by a wood elf can be entirely different from that same phrase spoken by an elf from the islands. As an example the word Andaali which comes from Limdar Aun-dah-jali Rain-warm-night is used to indicate the end of a conversation in aeldari and the beginning of one in soudari For - peoples/gatherings/a collection of that is better than a single Ael - elf/better than Lim - high/mighty/tall/proud Sou - wood/tree/rooted/caring Dari - gift/accomplishment Ya - a female (goddess of order) Tay - a male (god splinter) Bol - a type of tree (woody),  sturdy, bends under pressure instead of breaking Hin - a god who is a giant (big), but also proud or full of themselves, but also sometimes used to describe bugs Vun - a type of weapon (sword),  or the general motion of cutting, or cutting someone off, also used to say goodbye when angry Lak - the color of ignoring your friends for a while and sitting by themselves, also used for first person pronoun sometimes
text.1105: Living in the World Zurzok The language of the Aurks, it has a commanding presence, small vocabulary and simple grammar, allowing it to be easily picked up by new recruits and used in battle to give orders. Sounds There are 3 vowels in the language and 9 consonants O, Oo, eh, m, n, p, r, z, t, k, l, j Grammar Object’verb subject (Meat Eat, Dog) order where subject can be dropped and it is assumed to be in the form of a command. No conjugation in the language at all, time and place are specified if necessary. Adjectives can be doubled up for extra emphasis (Good-good, red-red) nouns can also be doubled up to represent that something is bigger or purer of that thing. Words Writing Orcish is not written, but where necessary they use the phonetics of nearby cultures to write out orcish words, generally scorbosi on paper and Dharob in rock. text.1111: Living in the World Dharob is distinctive by its large amount of Plosive ( p, b, t, d, k ,g) and fricative (F, Sh, V , H) consonants and relative lack of vowels. In fact the only time vowels are used is before or after a trill (R) noise and from writing they are generally omitted unless for the spelling of a name. Grammar Words are agglutinating, meaning they can be combined together under certain conditions, and dwarven word-smiths pride themselves on carrying entire conversations while only saying one word per breath. Pronouns are never dropped, even when leading with a name, and unless speaking to close friend it is considered rude not to address them by their full name as well Words Writing As Dharob is intended to be carved in stone, it is written in a series of straight lines. There are symbols in the writing for advancing more than one line down or up when reading, primarily used for conditionals in instruction manuals (if this happens, go to line 13, etc) however these symbols have been repurposed at times for some truly exciting poetry like “My Day” by the great poet Ahksan which reads “Work (Repeat from line 0)” Wogdharob A more relaxed and simplified version of the language spoken by the hill people of woglor. text.1145: Making Adventures Making adventures The following are some guidelines to making a fun Mortal Reins adventure. None of these are laws enshrined in stone - the whole point is having a world that shifts around the players so following anything dogmatically would get stale. Initial Hook Create an encounter for your players to get them straight into the action. At the start of the adventure you have the most control, so make the best use of it by throwing the characters into the situation. Ideally have the introduction meet the various locales and groups involved in the adventure, and make the players ask a question about a larger mystery. Have them guard a person or a caravan, or start at the beginning of a dungeon where someone they know has been kidnapped to, sent to the shop to inspect an artifact when a fight breaks out.. Just make sure there’s some action to bind the characters together and foreshadow the big problem of the adventure. After they have established ties, let them roam your world. Examples: · The player characters are caravanning with a big party to a nearby town when a few members fail to show up from after a routine stop. Each of the player characters volunteered to go look for the missing persons for their own reasons and are standing at the entrance of a cave where the tracks have led them. · The player characters are hired by a local noble to inspect the authenticity of an artifact a local merchant is selling. But as they are looking it over in the shop, a well armed adversary runs in to steal it, not afraid to use force to do so - who are they? · In a town ravaged by plague the body collectors are disappearing along with the bodies they collect. What is happening with them? The player characters have been hired to act as guards and investigators. Make it personal Take a look at the motivations and conflicts of the characters and fit them into your plot. If the player is a minority race or religion, make a location or faction based on that.  Do they know their own language, or do they only speak scorbosi? If the player has an internal conflict hammer it home with the situations provided. Make characters who comment with their opinion on different sides, or play out a situation which reflects it. An external conflict is even better. Is the mayor of the town allied with the dark lord who opposes one of the characters, or are they secretly working against said lord?
text.1148: Making Adventures shades of grey. Each group should have their own plots and a timeline in days until they succeed. This applies pressure for the players, and easily creates the timeline you need. Keep multiple plots running in the background, with a day tally and counter until a big reveal happens. Make sure there’s plenty of intermediate actions you can reveal to the players. Don’t be afraid to fudge the numbers a little especially if the players are interacting with one or more of these groups. Examples: · The necromancer wants to kill a local countess that spurned him in his youth · Day 1-3 cats are disappearing off the streets, which the locals find strange, as a whole array of different creatures emerge that go bump in the night · Day 4 a mysterious green glow is seen from the far side of town, where nobody goes · Day 5 an insane amalgamation of flesh and bone invades the streets, destroying everything on its path to the countess mansion - invariably including the players · The army commander wants to perform a coup against the local governor, believing him to be in the pocket of the enemy · Day 1 people are noticing a distinct lack of soldiers on the street, perhaps a larger amount of crime happening · Day 2 the general leads troops through the streets to the governor’s palace · Day 3 the general starts purging the government of people he doesn’t agree with, and persecuting a part of the populace · A nearby gang has plans for the neighborhood · Day 2 there’s a gathering of rogues in the city where the gang throws out its demands · Day 4 large amount of gang violence on the streets all over the city as the gang war commences. · Day 5 the victor of the gang war goes around asking for protection money (only interrupted by the insane flesh monster from above) · The local magistrate has decided to weed out corruption in the city · Day 1 He hires the players to look after a certain noble · Day 2 He has a verbal confrontation in the middle of the square with said noble; the players are invited to share any evidence they have gathered
text.1155: Making Adventures players can solve the problem. Be extremely hesitant to say “No” to any crazy scheme the players come up with, unless you have a concrete reason why that wouldn’t work; instead say “Y es, but… ” . Y ou can try to gently steer the players towards one of the solutions you thought through but be prepared to improvise. Solutions might seem extremely obvious to you and yet be completely missed by the players as they focus on something else, especially for investigations. To go around this, have a set of many clues prepared to each step that the players are expected to go to. Example: · The player characters need to rescue an important NPC from an army camp · Attack the camp directly - leading to a tough fight and potentially going on the run as the army rallies. · Prepare and sneak into the camp - which can go south easily, · Pretend they work for the army or civilians hired to bring supplies. · The players are tasked with finding out what’s happening about the disappearing bodies and body collectors - They are being stolen by ratmen on behalf of the necromancer · Follow the body collectors on their route and be jumped by the ratmen who work for the necromancer, then question any prisoners · Impersonate the collectors or bodies, to be captured and brought near the necromancers temple by the collectors themselves · Investigate similar rituals to learn that this has happened before · Take a look at the routes of the body collectors to see where they’re being ambushed, and deduce from that where the necromancer is Abstract Secrets In the same way as pieces of the story and setting, you can keep plots and secrets malleable by making them up beforehand without tying them to any specific person or location. For example, let’s say the GM wants to relate to the players that the thieves were Skeox from the thieves guild instead of writing down “Old Bigsy the tavern keep on the opposite side of the street saw the thieves in the night, and can tell the party they’re short,  have pointed ears, red eyes and claws, and were wearing blue cloaks” just jot down “the short thieves have pointed ears, red eyes and claws, and wear blue cloaks” .
text.1160: Making Adventures NPCs to inform the players about the world and make the players connect with the factions. Y ou’ll also want the different locales, ideally on a map, that the players can go to. These people are also your way of shifting gears throughout the adventure. If the players are doing particularly well, have them approach the player with a problem to solve, while if the players are doing terribly offer a devil’s bargain through one of the npcs. If the players are completely lost, as a last resort have an npc explain the current goings on, while if the players know exactly what’s going on, kill someone they know off to ratchet up the tension. Y ou don’t need a full background for each NPC, but you do want each one to be memorable for the players. Name, Origin and Job: Basic information that associates how they interact with the various power groups in the adventure. Acting Quirk: Y ou don’t have to do an accent, but something interesting for the character will help the players latch on to and distinguish the character. Motivation: This is what your character wants at this time, and can be as simple as survive or prosper and as complex as you can imagine. While the character can inform the players of their motivation, it’s more needed as a note for you to think about how they’ d react to anything the players do or happens in the world. Conflict: Completely optional, since these characters are more set dressing and less the focus of the story, but can be interesting for important NPCs to go through an arc as well. Pastimes: A list of activities the character is doing on a daily basis. Like with the acting quirk, it helps the player form a mental image of the character in their mind from a short description. Someone sharpening their knife collection will be remembered much differently to someone fortune telling with a flower. Ideal if the characters ask to find someone either with “I want to look for a shop keep” or “let’s find Jack and ask him about this” Character Interest:
text.1177: Making Adventures Running the game Don’t block the players Assume the player characters have a certain level of competence and don’t make them roll for basic tasks. Even if the task is difficult, only roll if a character is opposed or the task has a time limit. Even when rolling, don’t stop the game on a failure. Instead, let them succeed, but at a cost. Costs can include in game time, mind or body points, cash or meta currency. Don’t forget to remind the players they can permanently burn a fate point to succeed on a roll, no matter how bad it gets. Examples (Assume this is after a failed roll): Y ou can’t tell off hand what the dark scripture reads, but spending a few hours analyzing it in a library will reveal it. Y ou know a type of lockpick perfect for this specific lock but don’t have it on you at the moment - at the market you’re sure to find it though.The gap is slightly wider than you thought, and you barely reach out and grab onto the ledge on the other side. A brief look down at the crevasse leaves you terrified of what might have been - take 1d10 mind damage. Set the stakes, let the players take the risks and carry through The flip side of a dice failure only costing resources is the players can and will run out of resources. When this happens, they die by inches. Plans will fail, people will die, empires will crumble - that’s just the nature of the story. Fluid scene transitions Change up the pace of the game to keep it from being stale. From the time intervals to scene types, mix it up. If a fight is going bad for one side, suggest a pursuit as they run away, or transition straight from an investigation where each turn was a few hours to a social confrontation of a minute to 20 seconds per turn which goes sour and now it’s a combat with 5 seconds per turn and suddenly the bad guy is running away… and so it goes. This is particularly easy with social and physical combat. Characters are absolutely allowed to make social attacks during combat, which is a great way of knocking down some mind points, and a social confrontation can easily turn into combat if someone is angered or scared enough to draw sabers. This only counts as a scene change if the purpose of the scene changed and the scene will not go back - a warrior blowing his horn to intimidate the goblins in combat does not count as a new scene, but the goblins surrendering and being interrogated after a battle does.
text.1182: Making Adventures depending on the scale of the shakeup. It’s easy to make so many big events happen at the same time that the players lose track of what exactly is happening, and while this would still be a dynamic world, it wouldn’t be interesting as all the events blend into noise. Look for player input for people and locations Look for player input in your world and story. Regardless if this comes from in character interactions, or out of character discussions, this means your players are investing in your world - exactly what you want. If they’re looking for something or someone, allow them to not only find it, but add a detail to the world; who exactly is that thief they know in the city, and how do they know them? Then work the thing or person into the story by either adding it and making it a proper NPC with motivations and reactions, or choose one of your own characters that roughly fit the bill you haven’t had show up yet and swap in some basic details. Improvise The best laid plans go awry. Be prepared to think on your feet when that happens. Having a decent set of characters and factions helps out here as you can pull something from the box and throw it at the players to reconcile the current situation. Adding a little flavor When describing the world for the players (which is half the work of a Game Master) don’t be afraid to throw some memorable descriptions for the players to latch on to, and to evoke their imagination. This doesn’t mean you have to bust out the thesaurus and get a writing degree; Odds are the natural language that you and the players use is already the best way to communicate to them while they pay attention. Simply describe what they see, smell and feel in the place while adding in a few details. Something simple like describing the weather or the sky can go far in setting the mood, pulling the players out of their default mode and making them pay attention to the other details of the scene. Details are the lifeblood of moving a scene forward. Each detail provides clues to what is important. Details
text.1186: Making Adventures When improvising with the players, a situation might come up where the GM requires a character to go from a vague idea or few words on a scrap of paper to a fleshed out character where their numbers start to matter, either because they are engaged in a battle or even a simple contest with the players. Y ou could make the character like any other player character or adversary but that can be a time consuming effort. Alternatively you could look at a pre-generated character you do have that seems close enough to what you want from them. Or you could make all the numbers up; this is totally acceptable for background characters - engagement with the players is more important than consistency. If you do decide not to follow any process and make up the numbers, there’s a few things to keep in mind to make a believable character. Stats - don’t go too crazy here, keep the bonus close to 0, between, -3 and +5. The absolute majority of people have stat bonuses that are between -1 and less than +3, so anything above that is exceptional. This is important also because it modifies damage Skills - only write down the ones that will be relevant to play, and make them between 2 to 6 higher than the relevant stat Specialties - write in whatever seems relevant, choose a skill to base it off of and add 1 to 10 points to it. Keep in mind that 90% of specialties will be less than +3 and 95% will be less than +6 Y ou don’t need to go into detail on their secondary stats either, only coming up with them as they become relevant. Dodge, Perception, Consider - Range from 7 to 14 for most things, up to 18 for small and tiny creatures and less than that for large and huge creatures, based off their relevant stats Mind & Body - Range from 10 to 20 for most creatures, Up to 25 or 30 for exceptional ones Movement - keep it at 5 to 10 per move and 25 to 30 for running Armor - without magic, the highest armor a normal person can wear is 4 or 5, and the highest a strong warrior can wear is 7 to 9
text.1205: Foes & Monsters When making non player characters, Y ou’ll want to have relevant statistics of characters you expect your party to encounter. Y ou could go through the process of making a player character, but it would take a long time to create the many characters a GM could need for their encounters. Instead, you could make all the numbers for your adversaries up - this too is a fine way of going about it and it is detailed more in the Making Adventure chapter. The downfall there is a loss of verisimilitude by the players - the belief that they and their opponents are governed by the same system of laws. Seeing a Mortal man take more than 40-50 points of damage, for example, could tip the players off that the character isn’t playing by the same rules, as none of the player characters could achieve that level of survivability. Here’s a simplified system for making non-player characters: Statistics: Choose a difficulty level for the adversary from +1 to +5. This determines both their natural skill and their training. Their difficulty level represents their strongest stat, which is their core stat.Two other stats are less than their core stat by 1, that is their main line statOne stat is two less than their main line stat, that is their dump stat Weak: A Quarter of the population is +2, +2 +1 +1 -1 Average: The best in a small town, the types of people hired by large organizations and  are a +3 +3 +2 +2 +0 Strong: The best of the best, centurions, gladiators, knights are all a +4 +3 +3 +1 Legendary: Single individuals in the entire country are +5 Statistically +5 +4 +4 +2 Y ou can add their racial modifiers and adjust their stats by one or two points to give a specific character flavor, never going above their core stat. text.1268: Foes & Monsters In the darkest parts of the world, where even the wild things are afraid to roam, lurk monsters. They are the things of myth and nightmares - many people believe they are but tales and figments of imagination but that does not make them less real. Legend: A monster should not be sprung casually on an adventuring party. Have a build up to its presence through various clues and signs growing more and more obvious as the adventurers approach. By the time the adventurers encounter the monster they should have a good idea of its strengths and weaknesses. Because these things are game abstractions and not in the lore, feel free to tell the players more and more of its stat line if they do more and more research. Skills and Stats: Monsters universally have 0 empathy - although they may be able to communicate with others they do not think in a way that is understandable to mortals. Other than that they should have a scattering of stats higher than a player, but not my much. Their stat bonuses should range from +1 to +7 and their skills don’t have to match up with anything, choosing them as fits the monster. Occasionally you might desire a monster with an empathy score. Consider substituting the 0 in empathy with a 0 in another stat to make them alien to and different. If they have values in all four stats, strongly consider making them a powerful adversary instead. Size and Shape: With much more skills and specialties, monsters can and should be larger than adversaries. In addition, you can change their body - limb roll chart to represent their inhuman nature. The default works well for humanoid and quadruped characters but something like a snake might not have legs or a winged creature might suffer hits to its wings. Powers and Weakness: Monsters generally do not have equipment of their own, as they have neither the means of gaining it nor the desire to acquire it. Instead they have various powers. These are built from the spell list of various effects. Unlike arcane using mortals however, they do not need to focus or spend mind points to cast such a spell, instead it happens naturally. Each power is checked by a weakness that totally nullifies it, however that weakness is specific to a monster. Monsters have various subtypes and are shrouded in mystery, so a game master can feel free to use different weaknesses than those presented in books.
text.1271: Foes & Monsters When playing with a monster you’ll have to accept that your monster will be outnumbered by the players. Even if they are individually stronger, having a single enemy with the same or even greater number of XP than the party is worse than having a bunch of adversaries. In a match up of one creature versus the players, the amount of actions per side heavily favors the players. This can be mitigated in a few ways: · Size - A Monster can be larger than the players, and probably will be. This comes with a few benefits - a larger Body pool, stronger attacks and a small Area of Effect against players · Temporary Body - In the same Vein, monsters can have even more body points than players by virtue of having thicker unnatural skin, rocky outcroppings or anything else you can imagine· Extra Actions - The monster can permanently have the Haste power, or even past that, have many more actions than players. Even if a monster has four actions compared to the players it will likely be outnumbered, but this helps close the gap. · As a variant of giving the monster extra actions, consider a monster that is a permanently attached mount. This gives the monster more actions, and adds an arc to the fight as there is a part of the monster that is more difficult to hit (with the increased Dodge) · The magical core of the monster rider around inside a tendril filled fleshy body · A dryad nature spirit is permanently attached to a walking tree · Some sort of symbiote creature which rides a monster boar and shoots out tendrils of pure wrath · Followers - the core of the problem is the numbers problem, so have a monster summon some animated materials or mind controlled servants to even the odds a little bit. A few summoned skeletons or thralls, even of a tiny size, can split up the attention of the players · Superhuman stats - Monsters can have increased Stats, skills and specialties compared to mortal players. Scythe Sweep Reach 3m To Hit Roll +8 Damage 8+d10 AP Hit up to 3 Adjacent Size 1 Creatures Gameplan: The Quaburha has been locked away in the tomb for so long that it has grown bored of the task. If adventurers come before it, it will not attack immediately, instead warning them that they are transgressing the tomb and the path forward is forbidden (Provoke attack). It will offer to let them pass however, if they play a game of riddles with it. If the adventurers can stump it with their own riddles reducing it to 0 Mind, it will let them past. If it catches them cheating however, it will be enraged - and the concept of life or death is meaningless to it, so it’s likely to burn at least one of the characters beyond recovery with Fate or resurrection. In fact, if a character is downed, it will hurl curses at them and blast them with fire it’s next turn (Giving warning to the broken character’s companions to potentially rescue their body before it reduces it to ash, or make use of the Qabuuraha’s focus at their expense)
text.1291: Foes & Monsters Giant The giants wander the northern wastes, towering over the hills and glaciers there. They resemble people, except for their great size and naked featureless bodies. They seem to have some way of interacting with each other, but nothing they say can be made out except for a guttural growl that sounds like rocks scraping together. Size 5 - The giant stands roughly 16 to 20 meters tall.The Giant is so massive that any hits against it are likely to hit its feet unless it has fallen down or the characters have a way to hit another body part. text.1303: Foes & Monsters Titans: Not all monsters can be represented with a simple stat block. Some creatures are so mind bogglingly colossal that if they were to directly attack an adventurer it would be as if swatting a fly. Luckily they usually do not pay mind to individual mortals and stay far from civilization, deep in the wastes, jungles or tundra. While monsters are still told of in children’s fairy tales and nightmares, titans are unknown to all but a handful of people. Scale: Titans are huge - larger than the largest castles man has made and uncaring for such trifles in their wake. They are forces of nature and a place to explore, and an adventurer would have more luck digging through a mountain than they would chopping at a titan’s feet in an attempt to damage their body points. For this reason, titan stats and skills are not listed, although individual limbs and organs can be represented using monster rules, which usually have a size of 4 at the lowest.  Titans will not as a rule attack adventurers directly, but their mere presence can cause issues for those near them. Titanic Actions Titans are lumbering behemoths and an unstoppable force. To represent this they have an array of titanic powers. Each action has a windup time and acts like a spell. For each extra action the spell takes to be cast the spell gets 5 SP .  For these spells, the Area of Effect is tripled. Since the titan has no stats, it makes no roll to make this Titanic action happen, it just happens. If a part of the titan with stats performs this action, they can add their specialty to any bonus SP they get from their titanic action. If the titanic power activates after one action, make sure everyone knows about it - say something like “The dragon gets ready to bathe this area in flame, does anyone want to React?” Any reaction is valid to a Titanic Action, the characters can move, attack or improve their situation as they desire. If the titanic action happens on a subsequent turn, warn everyone in it’s effect area what’s about to happen.
text.1309: Foes & Monsters Colossus Arms and Legs - The Climb The limbs of a colossus are made of solid rock - they can not be penetrated except by extremely concentrated explosive or magic. Even the joints are reinforced. The sides are covered by vines and ritualistic carvings which allow for climbing up and down the titan, but this is a sheer climb that would exhaust many adventurers even with these plentiful arm and hand holds. To start this journey an  Athletics(Climb) check of 7 or more is required, but the checks get progressively harder, up to a difficulty of 15 to climb all the way to the top. Failure can mean a loss of mind and body points, exhaustion or even falling dozens of meters down. Titanic Action - Stomp or Smash It takes 3 turns to move as unstoppable force to deal 1d10 + 30 Damage in a rectangle with 15x30 meter sides, move everything 10 meters away from the epicenter and cause everyone in the zone to fall prone. On a successful Dexterity Save, the characters instead take 1d10 + 15 damage and do not fall prone. Body Once the body is reached, adventurers will note that there are entrances that can lead them inside the titan. On the inside the climb is much easier and they need not fear falling off and plummeting to their death. The inside is fashioned as a temple to the old gods. There are a series of inscriptions and traps here that can be overcome with successful Thievery(Traps) or Lore(Ancient) checks. Depending on the age and creation of the colossus there might be different specific traps, labyrinthine mazes or guardians present here. Making their way to the head on the inside the adventurers come to a stone slab gate that can be moved if they have previously found the colossus key - usually hidden in a separate temple to the god, or if an adventurer succeeds on a Smash(Inanimate Object) roll of 25 or Athletics(Move Weight) roll of 18. Otherwise the door has 60 hit points and a sufficiently powerful attack can break it. The door does not attack back, but weapons that hit it take the same amount of damage they inflict on themselves, and might break.
text.1350: Foes & Monsters roughly 20 miles per hour. When it reaches the surface it’s exit can be seen before it surfaces - not a whole lot of good that will do for those that see it, because for the sands above become like liquid from the bubbles it releases. Outside Once on the surface, the worm will continue to travel, swallowing anything in its path. It’s skin is made of half a meter of thick leather, although there are segments that are thicker and thinner, and it blasts jet streams of sand out until it gets all of them out of its gaps. If sufficient damage is done to the worm that the outside is penetrated, it will try to get back under the sand, to heal and come back later. If the characters find one of the small gaps in the worm they can try to force their way inside to enter the stomach or Internals Teethy maw If anything enters the maw, it has a slim chance for survival - the next 10 meters are packed with razor sharp teeth that chew up anything around. Everyone in the teeth suffers 10+d10 AP5 damage every turn that they are in there. To force their way through is a Difficulty 13 Athletics Challenge, alternatively the characters can Distract the worm somehow with a Difficulty 10 Challenge or if they do 30 points of damage the worm will vent the throat - the characters can choose to dive in or be spat back out. Belly of the Beast Once they make it past the maw, they enter the worm’s belly. It is a dark place where seldom things can be seen unless the adventurers brought a source of light such as a torch or spell. Everyone in the belly is affected by the Acid condition. Acid is a Damaging condition with intensity 2 (roll Inside Outside the belly, the rest of the worm is made of soft tissue that the character’s feet sink into like a soft mattress. Here the paths are lit up by glowing jelly that pulses through the membranes of flesh that pass as walls. The insides are coated with up to two dozen parasitic fungal growths, who form a symbiotic relationship with the worm, protecting its organs from anyone that ventures this far inside in exchange for slowly feeding off its nutrients.
text.1375: Foes & Monsters Armor 20 - Other than natural toughness, the dragon’s body is covered by armor as strong as metal plate. The first time a critical hit is scored against the dragon, one scale falls off. Mark down the number that was rolled - if that same number is rolled again the attack makes it to the leathery under skin of the armor. A Rarapis diamond (Extremely rare) forged with meteorite dust can create an effective weapon that destroys the scale 1 value above and below as well. Lord of Fire - The Dragon is the master of Fire and Wrath - he is immune to fire damage, whether from spells or catching fire. In addition, as a free action he burns out all poisons or bleeding coming from his body, meaning after one round all conditions on him end. As an entity with multiple stat blocks, each gets to act separately, with a total of 6 actions per turn. If any one part of the creature is defeated, the whole creature is wounded and will attempt to run away - if two parts are broken the dragon is slain.
